(1244, 'διανοημα', 1378, '1270', 'διανόημα', 'dianoēma', 1, 'thought, Lk. 11:17*'),
(1245, 'διανοια', 1379, '1271', 'διάνοια', 'dianoia', 12, 'pr. thought, intention; the mind, intellect, understanding, Mt. 22:37; Mk. 12:30; Lk. 10:27; an operation of the understanding, thought, imagination, Lk. 1:51; insight, comprehension, 1 Jn. 5:20; mode of thinking and feeling, disposition of mind and heart, the affection, Eph. 2:3; Col. 1:21 '),
(1246, 'διανοιγω', 1380, '1272', 'διανοίγω', 'dianoigō', 8, 'to open, Mk. 7:34, 35; Lk. 2:23; 24:31; Acts 7:56; met. to open the sense of a thing, explain, expound, Lk. 24:32; Acts 17:3; διανοίγειν τὸν νοῦν, τὴν καρδίαν, to open the mind, the heart, so as to understand and receive, Lk. 24:45; Acts 16:14*'),
(1247, 'διανυκτερευω', 1381, '1273', 'διανυκτερεύω', 'dianyktereuō', 1, 'to pass the night, spend the whole night, Lk. 6:12*'),
(1248, 'διανυω', 1382, '1274', 'διανύω', 'dianyō', 1, 'to complete, finish, Acts 21:7*'),
(1249, 'διαπαρατριβη', 1384, '3859', 'διαπαρατριβή', 'diaparatribē', 1, 'constant disputation, 1 Tim. 6:5*'),
(1250, 'διαπεραω', 1385, '1276', 'διαπεράω', 'diaperaō', 6, 'to pass through or over, Mt. 9:1; 14:34; Mk. 5:21; 6:53; Lk. 16:26; Acts 21:2*'),
(1251, 'διαπλεω', 1386, '1277', 'διαπλέω', 'diapleō', 1, 'to sail through or over, Acts 27:5*'),
(1252, 'διαπονεομαι', 1387, '1278', 'διαπονέομαι', 'diaponeomai', 2, 'pr. to be thoroughly exercised with labor; to be wearied; to be vexed, Acts 4:2; 16:18*'),
(1253, 'διαπορευομαι', 1388, '1279', 'διαπορεύομαι', 'diaporeuomai', 5, 'to go or pass through, Lk. 6:1; 13:22; Acts 16:4; to pass by, Lk. 18:36'),
(1254, 'διαπορεω', 1389, '1280', 'διαπορέω', 'diaporeō', 4, 'to be utterly at a loss; to be in doubt and perplexity, Lk. 9:7; Acts 2:12; 5:24; 10:17'),
(1255, 'διαπραγματευομαι', 1390, '1281', 'διαπραγματεύομαι', 'diapragmateuomai', 1, 'to despatch a matter thoroughly; to make profit in business, gain in trade, Lk. 19:15*'),
(1256, 'διαπριω', 1391, '1282', 'διαπρίω', 'diapriō', 2, 'to divide with a saw, saw asunder; to grate the teeth in a rage; pass. met. to be cut to the heart, to be enraged, Acts 5:33; 7:54*'),
(1257, 'διαρπαζω', 1395, '1283', 'διαρπάζω', 'diarpazō', 3, 'to plunder, spoil, pillage, Mt. 12:29; Mk. 3:27 (2x)*'),
(1258, 'διασαφεω', 1397, '1285', 'διασαφέω', 'diasapheō', 2, 'to make known, declare, tell plainly, or fully, Mt. 13:36; 18:31*'),
(1259, 'διασειω', 1398, '1286', 'διασείω', 'diaseiō', 1, 'pr. to shake thoroughly or violently; to harass, intimidate, extort from, Lk. 3:14*'),
(1260, 'διασκορπιζω', 1399, '1287', 'διασκορπίζω', 'diaskorpizō', 9, 'to disperse, scatter, Mt. 26:31; Mk. 14:27; to dissipate, waste, Lk. 15:13; 16:1; to winnow, or, to strew, Mt. 25:24, 26 '),
(1261, 'διασπαω', 1400, '1288', 'διασπάω', 'diaspaō', 2, 'to pull or tear asunder or in pieces, burst, Mk. 5:4; Acts 23:10*'),
(1262, 'διασπειρω', 1401, '1289', 'διασπείρω', 'diaspeirō', 3, 'to scatter abroad or in every direction, as seen; to disperse, Acts 8:1, 4; 11:19* '),
(1263, 'διασπορα', 1402, '1290', 'διασπορά', 'diaspora', 3, 'pr. a scattering, as of seed; dispersion; in NT meton. the dispersed portion of the Jews, specially termed the dispersion, Jn. 7:35; Jas. 1:1; 1 Pet. 1:1*'),
(1264, 'διαστελλω', 1403, '1291', 'διαστέλλω', 'diastellō', 8, 'to determine, issue a decision; to state or explain distinctly and accurately; hence, to admonish, direct, charge, command, Acts 15:24; Heb. 12:20; when followed by a negative clause, to interdict, prohibit, Mt. 16:30; Mk. 5:43 '),
(1265, 'διαστημα', 1404, '1292', 'διάστημα', 'diastēma', 1, 'interval, space, distance, Acts 5:7'),
(1266, 'διαστολη', 1405, '1293', 'διαστολή', 'diastolē', 3, 'distinction, difference, Rom. 3:22; 10:12; 1 Cor. 14:7*'),
(1267, 'διαστρεφω', 1406, '1294', 'διαστρέφω', 'diastrephō', 7, 'to distort, turn away; met. to pervert, corrupt, Mt. 17:17; Lk. 9:41; to turn out of the way, cause to make defection, Lk. 23:2; Acts 13:8; διεστραμμένος, perverse, corrupt, erroneous'),
(1268, 'διασωζω', 1407, '1295', 'διασῴζω', 'diasōzō', 8, 'to bring safely through; to convey in safety, Acts 23:24; pass. to reach a place or state of safety, Acts 27:43, 44; 28:1, 4; 1 Pet. 3:20; to heal, to restore to health, Mt. 14:36; Lk. 7:3*'),
(1269, 'διαταγη', 1408, '1296', 'διαταγή', 'diatagē', 2, 'an injunction, institute, ordinance, Rom. 13:2; Acts 7:53*'),
(1270, 'διαταγμα', 1409, '1297', 'διάταγμα', 'diatagma', 1, 'a mandate, commandment, ordinance, Heb. 11:23* '),
(1271, 'διαταρασσω', 1410, '1298', 'διαταράσσω', 'diatarassō', 1, 'to throw into a state of perturbation, to move or trouble greatly, Lk. 1:29*'),
(1272, 'διατασσω', 1411, '1299', 'διατάσσω', 'diatassō', 16, 'pr. to arrange, make a precise arrangement; to prescribe, 1 Cor. 11:34; 16:1; Tit. 1:5; to direct, Lk. 8:55; Acts 20:13; to charge, Mt. 11:1; to command, Acts 18:2; to ordain, Gal. 3:19 '),
(1273, 'διατελεω', 1412, '1300', 'διατελέω', 'diateleō', 1, 'to complete, finish; intrans. to continue, persevere, in a certain state or course of action, Acts 27:33*'),
(1274, 'διατηρεω', 1413, '1301', 'διατηρέω', 'diatēreō', 2, 'to watch carefully, guard with vigilance; to treasure up, Lk. 2:51; ἑαυτὸν ἐκ, to keep one’s self from, to abstain wholly from, Acts 15:29*'),
(1275, 'διατιθημι', 1416, '1303', 'διατίθημι', 'diatithēmi', 7, 'in NT only mid., so some list as διατίθεμαι, to arrange; to arrange according to one’s own mind; to make a disposition, to make a will; to settle the terms of a covenant, to ratify, Acts 3:25; Heb. 8:10; 10:16; to assign, Lk. 22:29'),
(1276, 'διατριβω', 1417, '1304', 'διατρίβω', 'diatribō', 9, 'pr. to rub, wear away by friction; met. to pass or spend time, to remain, stay, tarry, continue, Jn. 3:22; 11:54; Acts 12:19; 14:3, 28'),
(1277, 'διατροφη', 1418, '1305', 'διατροφή', 'diatrophē', 1, 'food, sustenance, 1 Tim. 6:8*'),
(1278, 'διαυγαζω', 1419, '1306', 'διαυγάζω', 'diaugazō', 1, 'to shine through, shine out, dawn, 2 Pet. 1:19*'),
(1279, 'διαυγης', 1420, '1305', 'διαυγής', 'diaugēs', 1, 'translucent, transparent, Rev. 21:21*'),
(1280, 'διαφερω', 1422, '1308', 'διαφέρω', 'diapherō', 13, 'to convey through, across, Mk. 11:16; to carry different ways or into different parts, separate; pass. to be borne, driven, or tossed hither and thither, Acts 27:27; to be proclaimed, published, Acts 13:49; intrans. met. to differ, 1 Cor. 15:41; to excel, be better or of greater value, be superior, Mt. 6:26; 10:31; impers. διαφέρει, it makes a difference, it is of consequence; with οὐδέν, it makes no difference, it is nothing, Gal. 2:6 '),
(1281, 'διαφευγω', 1423, '1309', 'διαφεύγω', 'diapheugō', 1, 'to flee through, escape by flight, Acts 27:42*'),
(1282, 'διαφημιζω', 1424, '1310', 'διαφημίζω', 'diaphēmizō', 3, 'to report, proclaim, publish, spread abroad, Mt. 9:31; 28:15; Mk. 1:45*'),
(1283, 'διαφθειρω', 1425, '1311', 'διαφθείρω', 'diaphtheirō', 6, 'to corrupt or destroy utterly; to waste, bring to decay, Lk. 12:33; 2 Cor. 4:16; to destroy, Rev. 8:9; 11:18 (2x); met. to corrupt, pervert utterly, 1 Tim. 6:5* '),
(1284, 'διαφθορα', 1426, '1312', 'διαφθορά', 'diaphthora', 6, 'corruption, dissolution, Acts 2:27, 31; 13:34, 35, 36, 37*'),
(1285, 'διαφορος', 1427, '1313', 'διάφορος', 'diaphoros', 4, 'different, diverse, of different kinds, Rom. 12:6; Heb. 9:10; excellent, superior, Heb. 1:4; 8:6*'),
(1286, 'διαφυλασσω', 1428, '1314', 'διαφυλάσσω', 'diaphylassō', 1, 'to keep or guard carefully or with vigilance; to guard, protect, Lk. 4:10*'),
(1287, 'διαχειριζω', 1429, '1315', 'διαχειρίζω', 'diacheirizō', 2, 'pr. to have in the hands, to manage; mid. later, to kill, Acts 5:30; 26:21*'),
(1288, 'διαχλευαζω', 1430, '1315', 'διαχλευάζω', 'diachleuazō', 1, 'to jeer outright, deride, Acts 2:13*'),
(1289, 'διαχωριζω', 1431, '1316', 'διαχωρίζω', 'diachōrizō', 1, 'to depart, go away, Lk. 9:33*'),
(1290, 'διδακτικος', 1434, '1317', 'διδακτικός', 'didaktikos', 2, 'apt or qualified to teach, 1 Tim. 3:2; 2 Tim. 2:24*'),
(1291, 'διδακτος', 1435, '1318', 'διδακτός', 'didaktos', 3, 'pr. taught, teachable, of things; in NT taught, of person, Jn. 6:45; 1 Cor. 2:13*'),
(1292, 'διδασκαλια', 1436, '1319', 'διδασκαλία', 'didaskalia', 21, 'the act or occupation of teaching, Rom. 12:7; 1 Tim. 4:13; information, instruction, Rom. 15:4; 2 Tim. 3:16; matter taught, precept, doctrine, Mt. 15:9; 1 Tim. 1:10 '),
(1293, 'διδασκαλος', 1437, '1320', 'διδάσκαλος', 'didaskalos', 59, 'a teacher, master, Rom. 2:20; in NT as an equivalent, to ῥαββί, Jn. 1:39 '),
(1294, 'διδασκω', 1438, '1321', 'διδάσκω', 'didaskō', 97, 'to teach, Mt. 4:23; 22:16; to teach or speak in a public assembly, 1 Tim. 2:12; to direct, admonish, Mt. 28:15; Rom. 2:21 '),
(1295, 'διδαχη', 1439, '1322', 'διδαχή', 'didachē', 30, 'instruction, the giving of instruction, teaching, Mk. 4:2; 12:38; instruction, what is taught, doctrine, Mt. 16:12; Jn. 7:16, 17; meton. mode of teaching and kind of doctrine taught, Mt. 7:28; Mk. 1:27 '),
(1296, 'διδραχμον', 1440, '1323', 'δίδραχμον', 'didrachmon', 2, 'a didrachmon or double drachma, a silver coin equal to the drachma of Alexandria, to two Attic drachmas, to two Roman denarii, and to the half-shekel of the Jews, Mt. 17:24 (2x)*'),
(1297, 'διδυμος', 1441, '1324', 'Δίδυμος', 'Didymos', 3, 'a twin; Didymus, the Greek equivalent to the name Thomas, Jn. 11:16; 20:24; 21:2*'),
(1298, 'διδωμι', 1443, '1325', 'δίδωμι', 'didōmi', 415, 'pluperfect, ἐδεδώκειν, to give, bestow, present, Mt. 4:9; 6:11; Jn. 3:16; 17:2, et al. freq.; to give, cast, throw, Mt. 7:6; to supply, suggest, Mt. 10:19; Mk. 13:11; to distribute alms, Mt. 19:21; Lk. 11:41; to pay tribute, etc., Mt. 22:17; Mk. 12:14; Lk. 20:22; to be the author or source of a thing, Lk. 12:51; Rom. 11:8; to grant, permit, allow, Acts 2:27; 13:35; Mt. 13:11; 19:11; to deliver to, entrust, commit to the charge of anyone, Mt. 25:15; Mk. 12:9; to give or deliver up, Lk. 22:19; Jn. 6:51; to reveal, teach, Acts 7:38; to appoint, constitute, Eph. 1:22; 4:11; to consecrate, devote, offer in sacrifice, 2 Cor. 8:5; Gal. 1:4; Rev. 8:3; to present, expose one’s self in a place, Acts 19:31; to recompense, Rev. 2:23; to attribute, ascribe, Jn. 9:24; Rev. 11:13; from the Hebrew, to place, put, fix, inscribe, Heb. 8:10; 10:16; to infix, impress, 2 Cor. 12:7; Rev. 13:16; to inflict, Jn. 18:22; 19:3; 2 Thess. 1:8; to give in charge, assign, Jn. 5:36; 17:4; Rev. 9:5; to exhibit, put forth, Mt. 24:24; Acts 2:19; to yield, bear fruit, Mt. 13:8; διδόναι ἐργασίαν, to endeavor, strive, Lk. 12:58; διδόναι ἀπόκρισιν, to answer, reply, Jn. 1:22; διδόναι τόπον, to give place, yield, Lk. 14:9; Rom. 12:19 '),
(1299, 'διεγειρω', 1444, '1326', 'διεγείρω', 'diegeirō', 6, 'to arouse or awake thoroughly, Mt. 1:24; Mk. 4:38, 39; Lk. 8:24; pass. to be raised, excited, agitated, as a sea, Jn. 6:18; met. to stir up, arouse, animate, 2 Pet. 1:13; 3:1'),
(1300, 'διενθυμεομαι', 1445, '1326', 'διενθυμέομαι', 'dienthumeomai', 1, 'to revolve thoroughly in the mind, consider carefully, ponder, reflect, Acts 10:19*');
INSERT INTO `mounce` (`id`, `word`, `gkNr`, `strongs`, `lemma`, `transliteration`, `frequenceyCount`, `definition`) VALUES
(1301, 'διεξοδος', 1447, '1327', 'διέξοδος', 'diexodos', 1, 'a passage throughout; a line of road, a thoroughfare, Mt. 22:9*'),
(1302, 'διερμηνευτης', 1449, '1328', 'διερμηνευτής', 'diermēneutēs', 1, 'an interpreter, 1 Cor. 14:28*'),
(1303, 'διερμηνευω', 1450, '1329', 'διερμηνεύω', 'diermēneuō', 6, 'to explain, interpret, translate, Lk. 24:27; Acts 9:36; 1 Cor. 14:5, 13, 27; to be able to interpret, 1 Cor. 12:30*'),
(1304, 'διερχομαι', 1451, '1330', 'διέρχομαι', 'dierchomai', 43, 'to pass through, Mk. 10:25; Lk. 4:30; to pass over, cross, Mk. 4:35; Lk. 8:22; to pass along, Lk. 19:4; to proceed, Lk. 2:15; Acts 9:38; to travel through or over a country, wander about, Mt. 12:43; Lk. 9:6; to transfix, pierce, Lk. 2:35; to spread abroad, be prevalent, as a rumor, Lk. 5:15; met. to extend to, Rom. 5:12 '),
(1305, 'διερωταω', 1452, '1331', 'διερωτάω', 'dierōtaō', 1, 'to sift by questioning, of persons; in NT, of things, to ascertain by inquiry, Acts 10:17*'),
(1306, 'διετης', 1453, '1332', 'διετής', 'dietēs', 1, 'of two years; of the age of two years, Mt. 2:16*'),
(1307, 'διετια', 1454, '1333', 'διετία', 'dietia', 2, 'the space of two years, Acts 24:27; 28:30*'),
(1308, 'διηγεομαι', 1455, '1334', 'διηγέομαι', 'diēgeomai', 8, 'pr. to lead throughout; to declare thoroughly, detail, recount, relate, tell, Mk. 5:16; 9:9; Lk. 8:39; Acts 8:33; Heb. 11:32'),
(1309, 'διηγησις', 1456, '1335', 'διήγησις', 'diēgēsis', 1, 'a narration, relation, history, Lk. 1:1*'),
(1310, 'διηνεκης', 1457, '1336', 'διηνεκής', 'diēnekēs', 4, 'continuous, uninterrupted; εἰς τὸ διηνεκές, perpetually, Heb. 7:3; 10:1, 12, 14*'),
(1311, 'διθαλασσος', 1458, '1337', 'διθάλασσος', 'dithalassos', 1, 'surrounded on both sides by the sea; τόπος διθάλασσος, a shoal or sand-bank formed by the confluence of opposite currents, Acts 27:41*'),
(1312, 'διικνεομαι', 1459, '1338', 'διϊκνέομαι', 'diikneomai', 1, 'to go or pass through; to penetrate, Heb. 4:12*'),
(1313, 'διιστημι', 1460, '1339', 'διίστημι', 'diistēmi', 3, 'to set at an interval, apart; to station at an interval from a former position, Acts 27:28; intrans. to stand apart; to depart, be parted, Lk. 24:51; of time, to intervene, be interposed, Lk. 22:59*'),
(1314, 'διισχυριζομαι', 1462, '1340', 'διϊσχυρίζομαι', 'diischurizomai', 2, 'to feel or express reliance; to affirm confidently, insist, Lk. 22:59; Acts 12:15*'),
(1315, 'δικαιοκρισια', 1464, '1341', 'δικαιοκρισία', 'dikaiokrisia', 1, 'just or righteous judgment, Rom. 2:5*'),
(1316, 'δικαιος', 1465, '1342', 'δίκαιος', 'dikaios', 79, 'just, equitable, fair, Mt. 20:4; Lk. 12:57; Jn. 5:30; Col. 4:1; of persons, just, righteous, absolutely, Jn. 17:25; Rom. 3:10, 26; 2 Tim. 4:8; 1 Pet. 3:18; 1 Jn. 1:9; 2:1, 29; Rev. 16:5; righteous by account and acceptance, Rom. 2:13; 5:19; in ordinary usage, just, upright, innocent, pious, Mt. 5:45; 9:13, et al. freq.; ὁ δίκαιος, the Just One, one of the distinctive titles of the Messiah, Acts 3:14; 7:52; 22:14 '),
(1317, 'δικαιοσυνη', 1466, '1343', 'δικαιοσύνη', 'dikaiosynē', 92, 'fair and equitable dealing, justice, Acts 17:31; Heb. 11:33; Rom. 9:28; integrity, virtue, Lk. 1:75; Eph. 5:9; in NT generosity, alms, 2 Cor. 9:10, v.r.; Mt. 6:1; piety, godliness, Rom. 6:13; investiture with the attribute of righteousness, acceptance as righteous, justification, Rom. 4:11; 10:4, et al. freq.; a provision or mean for justification, Rom. 1:17; 2 Cor. 3:9; an instance of justification, 2 Cor. 5:21 '),
(1318, 'δικαιοω', 1467, '1344', 'δικαιόω', 'dikaioō', 39, 'pr. to make or render right or just; mid. to act with justice, Rev. 22:11; to avouch to be good and true, to vindicate, Mt. 11:19; Lk. 7:29; to set forth as good and just, Lk. 10:29; 16:15; in NT to hold as guiltless, to accept as righteous, to justify, Rom. 3:26, 30; 4:5; 8:30, 33; pass. to be held acquitted, to be cleared, Acts 13:39; Rom. 3:24; 6:7; to be approved, to stand approved, to stand accepted, Rom. 2:13; 3:20, 28 '),
(1319, 'δικαιωμα', 1468, '1345', 'δικαίωμα', 'dikaiōma', 10, 'pr. a rightful act, act of justice, equity; a sentence, of condemnation, Rev. 15:4; in NT, of acquittal, justification, Rom. 5:16; a decree, law, ordinance, Lk. 1:6; Rom. 1:32; 2:26; 8:4; Heb. 9:1, 10; a meritorious act, an instance of perfect righteousness, Rom. 5:18; Rev. 19:8* '),
(1320, 'δικαιως', 1469, '1346', 'δικαίως', 'dikaiōs', 5, 'justly, with strict justice, 1 Pet. 2:23; deservedly, Lk. 23:41; as it is right, fit or proper, 1 Cor. 15:34; uprightly, honestly, piously, religiously, 1 Thess. 2:10; Tit. 2:12*'),
(1321, 'δικαιωσις', 1470, '1347', 'δικαίωσις', 'dikaiōsis', 2, 'pr. a making right or just; a declaration of right or justice; a judicial sentence; in NT, acquittal, acceptance, justification, Rom. 4:25; 5:18*'),
(1322, 'δικαστης', 1471, '1348', 'δικαστής', 'dikastēs', 2, 'a judge, Acts 7:27, 35*'),
(1323, 'δικη', 1472, '1349', 'δίκη', 'dikē', 3, 'right, justice; in NT judicial punishment, vengeance, 2 Thess. 1:9; Jude 7; sentence of punishment, judgment, Acts 25:15; personified, the goddess of justice or vengeance, Nemesis, Paena, Acts 28:4'),
(1324, 'δικτυον', 1473, '1350', 'δίκτυον', 'diktyon', 12, 'a net, fishing-net, Mt. 4:20, 21 '),
(1325, 'διλογος', 1474, '1351', 'δίλογος', 'dilogos', 1, 'pr. saying the same thing twice; in NT double-tongued, speaking one thing and meaning another, deceitful in words, 1 Tim. 3:8*'),
(1326, 'διο', 1475, '1352', 'διό', 'dio', 53, 'inferential conj., on which account, wherefore, therefore, Mt. 27:8; 1 Cor. 12:3'),
(1327, 'διοδευω', 1476, '1353', 'διοδεύω', 'diodeuō', 2, 'to travel through a place, traverse, Lk. 8:1; Acts 17:1'),
(1328, 'διονυσιος', 1477, '1354', 'Διονύσιος', 'Dionysios', 1, 'Dionysius, pr. name, Acts 17:34*'),
(1329, 'διοπερ', 1478, '1355', 'διόπερ', 'dioper', 2, 'inferential conj., on this very account, for this very reason, wherefore, 1 Cor. 8:13; 10:14*'),
(1330, 'διοπετης', 1479, '1356', 'διοπετής', 'diopetēs', 1, 'which fell from Jupiter, or heaven; τοῦ διοπετοῦς, i.e. ἀγάλματος, image or statue; for discussion of ellipsis see grammars, Acts 19:35*'),
(1331, 'διορθωμα', 1480, '1326', 'διόρθωμα', 'diorthōma', 1, 'correction, emendation, reformation, Acts 24:2*'),
(1332, 'διορθωσις', 1481, '1357', 'διόρθωσις', 'diorthōsis', 1, 'a complete rectification, reformation, Heb. 9:10'),
(1333, 'διορυσσω', 1482, '1358', 'διορύσσω', 'dioryssō', 4, 'to dig or break through, Mt. 6:19, 20; 24:43; Lk. 12:39*'),
(1334, 'διοσκουροι', 1483, '1359', 'Διόσκουροι', 'Dioskouroi', 1, 'the Dioscuri, Castor and Pollux, sons of Jupiter by Leda, and patrons of sailors, Acts 28:11*'),
(1335, 'διοτι', 1484, '1360', 'διότι', 'dioti', 23, 'on the account that, because, Lk. 2:7; 21:28; in as much as, Lk. 1:13; Acts 18:10'),
(1336, 'διοτρεφης', 1485, '1361', 'Διοτρέφης', 'Diotrephēs', 1, 'Diotrephes, pr. name, 3 Jn. 9*'),
