(1600, 'ελαμιτης', 1780, '1639', 'Ἐλαμίτης', 'Elamitēs', 1, 'an Elamite; an inhabitant of Elam, a province of Persia, Acts 2:9*'),
(1601, 'ελασσων', 1781, '1640', 'ἐλάσσων', 'elassōn', 4, 'ἐλάττων (G1784) is the Attic form of this word. Twice it is used with σσ (Jn. 2:10; Rom. 9:12) and twice with ττ (1 Tim. 5:9; Heb. 7:7). It is used as the comparative of μικρός, less; less in age, younger, Rom. 9:12; less in dignity, inferior, Heb. 7:7; less in quality, inferior, worse, Jn. 2:10; 1 Tim. 5:9*'),
(1602, 'ελαττονεω', 1782, '1641', 'ἐλαττονέω', 'elattoneō', 1, 'trans. to make less; intrans. to be less, inferior; to have too little, want, lack, 2 Cor. 8:15*'),
(1603, 'ελαττοω', 1783, '1642', 'ἐλαττόω', 'elattoō', 3, 'to make less or inferior, Heb. 2:7; pass. to be made less or inferior, Heb. 2:9; to decline in importance, Jn. 3:30*'),
(1604, 'ελαυνω', 1785, '1643', 'ἐλαύνω', 'elaunō', 5, 'to drive, urge forward, spur on, Lk. 8:29; Jas. 3:4; 2 Pet. 2:17; to impel a vessel by oars, to row, Mk. 6:48; Jn. 6:19*'),
(1605, 'ελαφρια', 1786, '1644', 'ἐλαφρία', 'elaphria', 1, 'lightness in weight; hence, lightness of mind, levity, 2 Cor. 1:17*'),
(1606, 'ελαφρος', 1787, '1645', 'ἐλαφρός', 'elaphros', 2, 'light, not heavy, Mt. 11:30; 2 Cor. 4:17*'),
(1607, 'ελαχιστος', 1788, '1646,1647', 'ἐλάχιστος', 'elachistos', 14, 'used as the superlative of μικρός, smallest, least, Mt. 2:6; 5:19 '),
(1608, 'ελεαζαρ', 1789, '1648', 'Ἐλεάζαρ', 'Eleazar', 2, 'Eleazar, pr. name, indecl., Mt. 1:15*'),
(1609, 'ελεαω', 1790, '1648', 'ἐλεάω', 'eleaō', 4, 'see ἐλεέω, have mercy on, Rom. 9:16; 12:8; Jude 22, 23*'),
(1610, 'ελεγμος', 1791, '1648', 'ἐλεγμός', 'elegmos', 1, 'reproof, 2 Tim. 3:16, a later equivalent to ἔλεγχος*'),
(1611, 'ελεγξις', 1792, '1649', 'ἔλεγξις', 'elenxis', 1, 'reproof, rebuke, 2 Pet. 2:16*'),
(1612, 'ελεγχος', 1793, '1650', 'ἔλεγχος', 'elenchos', 1, 'pr. a trial in order to proof, a proof; meton. a certain persuasion, Heb. 11:1*'),
(1613, 'ελεγχω', 1794, '1651', 'ἐλέγχω', 'elenchō', 17, 'to put to proof, to test; to convict, Jn. 8:46; Jas. 2:9; to refute, confute, 1 Cor. 14:24; Tit. 1:9; to detect, lay bare, expose, Jn. 3:20; Eph. 5:11, 13; to reprove, rebuke, Mt. 18:15; Lk. 3:19; 1 Tim. 5:20; to discipline, chastise, Heb. 12:5; Rev. 3:19; pass. to experience conviction, Jn. 3:20; 1 Cor. 14:24 '),
