(2132, 'εφημερια', 2389, '2183', 'ἐφημερία', 'ephēmeria', 2, 'pr. daily course; the daily service of the temple; a class of priests to which the daily service for a week was allotted in rotation, Lk. 1:5, 8*'),
(2133, 'εφημερος', 2390, '2184', 'ἐφήμερος', 'ephēmeros', 1, 'lasting for a day; daily sufficient for a day, necessary for every day, Jas. 2:15*'),
(2134, 'εφικνεομαι', 2391, '2185', 'ἐφικνέομαι', 'ephikneomai', 2, 'to come or reach to, to reach a certain point or end; to reach, arrive at, 2 Cor. 10:13, 14*'),
(2135, 'εφιστημι', 2392, '2186', 'ἐφίστημι', 'ephistēmi', 21, 'trans. to place upon, over, close by; intrans. to stand by or near, Lk. 2:38; 4:39; to come suddenly upon, Lk. 2:9; 24:4; to come upon, assault, Acts 6:12; 17:5; to come near, approach, Lk. 10:40; to impend, be instant, to be at hand, 1 Thess. 5:3; to be present, Acts 28:2; to be pressing, urgent, earnest, 2 Tim. 4:2 '),
(2136, 'εφοραω', 2393, '1896', 'ἐφοράω', 'ephoraō', 2, 'a proposed lexical form for the second aorist ἐπεῖδον'),
(2137, 'εφραιμ', 2394, '2187', 'Ἐφραίμ', 'Ephraim', 1, 'Ephraim, pr. name, indecl. Jn. 11:54*. See PhotoGuide.'),
(2138, 'εφφαθα', 2395, '2188', 'ἐφφαθά', 'ephphatha', 1, 'Aramaic, be thou opened, Mk. 7:34*'),
(2139, 'εχθες', 2396, '5504', 'ἐχθές', 'echthes', 3, 'yesterday, Jn. 4:52; Acts 7:28; Heb. 13:8*'),
(2140, 'εχθρα', 2397, '2189', 'ἔχθρα', 'echthra', 6, 'enmity, discord, feud, Lk. 23:12; Gal. 5:20; alienation, Eph. 2:14, 16; a principle or state of enmity, Rom. 8:7; Jas. 4:4*'),
(2141, 'εχθρος', 2398, '2190', 'ἐχθρός', 'echthros', 32, 'hated, under disfavor, Rom. 11:28; inimical, hostile, Mt. 13:28; Col. 1:21; as a subst., an enemy, adversary, Mt. 5:43, 44; 10:36; Lk. 27:35 '),
(2142, 'εχιδνα', 2399, '2191', 'ἔχιδνα', 'echidna', 5, 'a viper, poisonous serpent, Acts 28:3; used also fig. of persons, Mt. 3:7; 12:34; 23:33; Lk. 3:7*'),
(2143, 'εχω', 2400, '2192', 'ἔχω', 'echō', 708, 'pluperfect., ἐσχήκειν, to hold, Rev. 1:16; to seize, possess a person, Mk. 16:8; to have, possess, Mt. 7:29, et al. freq.; to have, have ready, be furnished with, Mt. 5:23; Jn. 5:36; 6:68; to have as a matter of crimination, Mt. 5:23; Mk. 11:25; to have at command, Mt. 27:65; to have the power, be able, Mt. 18:25; Lk. 14:14; Acts 4:14; to have in marriage, Mt. 14:4; to have, be affected by, subjected to, Mt. 3:14; 12:10; Mk. 3:10; Jn. 12:48; 15:22, 24; 16:21, 22; Acts 23:29; 1 Tim. 5:12; Heb. 7:28; 1 Jn. 1:8; 4:18; χάραν ἔχειν, to feel gratitude, be thankful, 1 Tim. 1:12; 2 Tim. 1:3; Phlm. 7; to hold, esteem, regard, Mt. 14:5; Lk. 14:18, 19; to have or hold as an object of knowledge, faith, or practice, Jn. 5:38, 42; 14:21; 1 Jn. 5:12; 2 Jn. 9; to hold on in entire possession, to retain, Rom. 15:4; 2 Tim. 1:13; Heb. 12:28; intrans. with adverbs or adverbial expression, to be, to fare, Mt. 9:12; Mk. 2:17; 5:23; Lk. 5:31; Jn. 4:52; Acts 7:1; 12:15; 15:36; 21:13; 2 Cor. 10:6; 12:14; 1 Tim. 5:25; 1 Pet. 4:5; τὸ νῦν ἔχον, for the present; in NT ἔχειν ἐν γαστρί, to be pregnant, Mt. 1:18; as also ἔχειν κοίτην, Rom. 9:10; ἔχειν δαιμόνιον, to be possessed, Mt. 11:18; of time, to have continued, to have lived, Jn. 5:5, 6; 8:57; of space, to embrace, be distant, Acts 1:12; mid. pr. to hold by, cling to; hence, to border upon, be next, Mk. 1:38; Lk. 13:33; Acts 20:15; 21:26; to tend immediately to, Heb. 6:9 '),
(2144, 'εως', 2401, '2193', 'ἕως', 'heōs', 146, 'can function as an improper prep., while, as long as, Jn. 9:4; until, Mt. 2:9; Lk. 15:4; as also in NT ἕως οὗ, ἕως ὅτου, Mt. 5:18, 26; ἕως ἄρτι, until now, Mt. 11:12; ἕως πότε, until when, how long, Mt. 17:17; ἕως σήμερον, until this day, to this time, 2 Cor. 3:15; as a prep. of time, until, Mt. 24:21; of place, unto, even to, Mt. 11:23; Lk. 2:15; ἕως ἄνω, to the brim, Jn. 2:7; ἕως εἰς, even to, as far as, Lk. 24:50; ἕως κάτω, to the bottom; ἕως ὥδε, to this place, Lk. 23:5; of state, unto, even to, Mt. 26:38; of number, even, so much as, Rom. 3:12, et al. freq.'),
(2145, 'ζαβουλων', 2404, '2194', 'Ζαβουλών', 'Zaboulōn', 3, 'Zebulun, pr. name, indecl., an Israelite tribe, Mt. 4:13, 15; Rev. 7:8*'),
(2146, 'ζακχαιος', 2405, '2195', 'Ζακχαῖος', 'Zakchaios', 3, 'Zaccheus, pr. name, Lk. 19:2, 5, 8*'),
(2147, 'ζαρα', 2406, '2196', 'Ζάρα', 'Zara', 1, 'Zerah, pr. name, indecl., Mt. 1:3*'),
(2148, 'ζαχαριας', 2408, '2197', 'Ζαχαρίας', 'Zacharias', 11, 'Zacharias, pr. name. (1) Son of Barachias, Mt. 23:35; Lk. 11:51. (2) Father of Jn. the Baptist, Lk. 1:5'),
(2149, 'ζαω', 2409, '2198', 'ζάω', 'zaō', 140, 'to live, to be possessed of vitality, to exercise the functions of life, Mt. 27:63; Acts 17:28; τὸ ζῆν, life, Heb. 2:15; to have means of subsistence, 1 Cor. 9:14; to live, to pass existence in a specific manner, Lk. 2:36; 15:13; to be instinct with life and vigor; hence, ζῶν, living, an epithet of God, in a sense peculiar to Himself; ἐλπὶς ζῶσα, a living hope vigor and constancy, 1 Pet. 1:3; ὕδωρ ζῶν, living water in respect of a full and unfailing flow, Jn. 4:10, 11; to be alive with cheered and hopeful feelings, 1 Thess. 3:8; to be alive in a state of salvation from spiritual death, 1 Jn. 4:9 '),
(2150, 'ζεβεδαιος', 2411, '2199', 'Ζεβεδαῖος', 'Zebedaios', 12, 'Zebedee, pr. name, the father of Jas. and John, Mt. 4:21; Mk. 10:35; Lk. 5:10; Jn. 21:1*'),
(2151, 'ζεστος', 2412, '2200', 'ζεστός', 'zestos', 3, 'pr. boiled; boiling, boiling hot; met. glowing with zeal, fervent, Rev. 3:15, 16*'),
(2152, 'ζευγος', 2414, '2201', 'ζεῦγος', 'zeugos', 2, 'a yoke of animals; a pair, couple, Lk. 2:24; 14:19*'),
(2153, 'ζευκτηρια', 2415, '2202', 'ζευκτηρία', 'zeuktēria', 1, 'a fastening, band, Acts 27:40*'),
(2154, 'ζευς', 2416, '2203', 'Ζεύς', 'Zeus', 2, 'the supreme god of the Greeks answering to the Jupiter of the Romans, Acts 14:12, 13*'),
(2155, 'ζεω', 2417, '2204', 'ζέω', 'zeō', 2, 'to boil, to be hot, in NT met. to be fervent, ardent, zealous, Acts 18:25; Rom. 12:11*'),
(2156, 'ζηλευω', 2418, '2204', 'ζηλεύω', 'zēleuō', 1, 'to be zealous, earnest, eager, Rev. 3:19*'),
(2157, 'ζηλος', 2419, '2205', 'ζῆλος', 'zēlos', 16, 'generous rivalry; noble aspiration; in NT zeal, ardor in behalf of, ardent affection, Jn. 2:17; Rom. 10:2; in a bad sense, jealousy, envy, malice, Acts 13:45; Rom. 13:13; indignation, wrath, Acts 5:17 '),
(2158, 'ζηλοω', 2420, '2206', 'ζηλόω', 'zēloō', 11, 'to have strong affection towards, be ardently devoted to, 2 Cor. 11:2; to make a show of affection and devotion towards, Gal. 4:17; to desire earnestly, aspire eagerly after, 1 Cor. 12:31; 14:1, 39; absol. to be fervent, to be zealous, Rev. 3:19; to be jealous, envious, spiteful, Acts 7:9; 17:5; 1 Cor. 13:4; Jas. 4:2; pass. to be an object of warm regard and devotion, Gal. 4:18 ');
INSERT INTO `mounce` (`id`, `word`, `gkNr`, `strongs`, `lemma`, `transliteration`, `frequenceyCount`, `definition`) VALUES
(2159, 'ζηλωτης', 2421, '2207,2208', 'ζηλωτής', 'zēlōtēs', 8, 'pr. a generous rival, an imitator; in NT an aspirant, 1 Cor. 14:12; Tit. 2:14; a devoted adherent, a zealot, Acts 21:20; 22:3; Gal. 1:14'),
(2160, 'ζημια', 2422, '2209', 'ζημία', 'zēmia', 4, 'damage, loss, detriment, Acts 27:10, 21; Phil. 3:7, 8*'),
(2161, 'ζηνας', 2424, '2211', 'Ζηνᾶς', 'Zēnas', 1, 'Zenas, pr. name, Tit. 3:13*'),
(2162, 'ζητεω', 2426, '2212', 'ζητέω', 'zēteō', 117, 'to seek, look for, Mt. 18:12; Lk. 2:48, 49; to search after, Mt. 13:45; to be on the watch for, Mt. 26:16; to pursue, endeavor to obtain, Rom. 2:7; 1 Pet. 3:11; to desire, wish, want, Mt. 12:47; to seek, strive for, Mt. 6:33; to endeavor, Mt. 21:46; to require, demand, ask for, Mk. 8:11; Lk. 11:16; 12:48; to inquire or ask questions, question, Jn. 16:19; to deliberate, Mk. 11:18; Lk. 12:29; in NT from Hebrew, ζητεῖν τὴν ψυχήν, to seek the life of any one, to seek to kill, Mt. 2:20 '),
(2163, 'ζητημα', 2427, '2213', 'ζήτημα', 'zētēma', 5, 'a question; a subject of debate or controversy, Acts 15:2; 18:15; 23:29; 25:19; 26:3*'),
(2164, 'ζητησις', 2428, '2214', 'ζήτησις', 'zētēsis', 7, 'a seeking; an inquiry, a question; a dispute, debate, discussion, Jn. 3:25; 1 Tim. 6:4; a subject of dispute or controversy, Acts 15:2, 7; 25:20; 2 Tim. 2:23; Tit. 3:9'),
(2165, 'ζιζανιον', 2429, '2215', 'ζιζάνιον', 'zizanion', 8, 'zizanium, darnel, spurious wheat, a plant found in Palestine, which resembles wheat both in its stalk and grain, but is worthless, Mt. 13:25, 26, 27, 29, 30, 36, 38, 40*'),
(2166, 'ζοροβαβελ', 2431, '2216', 'Ζοροβαβέλ', 'Zorobabel', 3, 'Zorobabel, pr. name, indecl. (Ezra 2:2; 3:8), Mt. 1:12, 13; Lk. 3:27*'),
(2167, 'ζοφος', 2432, '2217', 'ζόφος', 'zophos', 5, 'gloom, thick darkness, Heb. 12:18; 2 Pet. 2:4, 17; Jude 6, 13*'),
(2168, 'ζυγος', 2433, '2218', 'ζυγός', 'zygos', 6, 'also spelled ζυγόν, ου, τό (n-2c), pr. a cross bar or band; a yoke; met. a yoke of servile condition, 1 Tim. 6:1; a yoke of service or obligation, Mt. 11:29, 30; Acts 15:10; Gal. 5:1; the beam of a balance; a balance, Rev. 6:5*'),
(2169, 'ζυμη', 2434, '2219', 'ζύμη', 'zymē', 13, 'leaven, yeast, Mt. 16:12; 13:33; met. leaven of the mind and conduct, by a system of doctrine or morals, used in a bad sense, Mt. 16:6, 11; 1 Cor. 5:6 '),
(2170, 'ζυμοω', 2435, '2220', 'ζυμόω', 'zymoō', 4, 'to leaven, cause to ferment, Mt. 13:33; Lk. 13:21; 1 Cor. 5:6; Gal. 5:9*'),
(2171, 'ζωγρεω', 2436, '2221', 'ζωγρέω', 'zōgreō', 2, 'pr. to take alive, take prisoner in war instead of killing; to take captive, enthral, 2 Tim. 2:26; also, to catch animals, as fish; in which sense it is used figuratively, Lk. 5:10*'),
(2172, 'ζωη', 2437, '2222', 'ζωή', 'zōē', 135, 'life, living existence, Lk. 16:25; Acts 17:25; in NT spiritual life of deliverance from the proper penalty of sin, which is expressed by θάνατος, Jn. 6:51; Rom. 5:18; 6:4; the final life of the redeemed, Mt. 25:46; life, source of spiritual life, Jn. 5:39; 11:25; Col. 3:4 '),
(2173, 'ζωνη', 2438, '2223', 'ζώνη', 'zōnē', 8, 'a zone, belt, girdle, Mt. 3:4; 10:9; Mk. 1:6; 6:8; Acts 21:11; Rev. 1:13; 15:6*'),
(2174, 'ζωννυμι', 2439, '2224', 'ζώννυμι', 'zōnnymi', 3, 'also spelled ζωννύω, to gird, gird on, put on one’s girdle, Jn. 21:18 (2x), Acts 12:8*'),
(2175, 'ζωογονεω', 2441, '2225', 'ζῳογονέω', 'zōiogoneō', 3, 'pr. to bring forth living creatures; in NT to preserve alive, save, Lk. 17:33; Acts 7:19; 1 Tim. 6:13*'),
(2176, 'ζωον', 2442, '2226', 'ζῷον', 'zōon', 23, 'a living creature, animal, Heb. 13:11; 2 Pet. 2:12 '),
(2177, 'ζωοποιεω', 2443, '2227', 'ζῳοποιέω', 'zōiopoieō', 11, 'pr. to engender living creatures; to quicken, make alive, Rom. 4:17; 8:11; 1 Cor. 15:36; in NT met. to quicken with the life of salvation, Jn. 6:63; 2 Cor. 3:6 '),
(2178, 'η', 2445, '2228', 'ἤ', 'ē', 343, 'can function as a conj (298x), either, or, Mt. 6:24; after comparatives, and ἄλλος, ἕτερος, expressed or implied, than, Mt. 10:15; 18:8; Acts 17:21; 24:21; intensive after ἀλλά and πρίν, Lk. 12:51; Mt. 1:18; it also serves to point an interrogation, Rom. 3:29'),
(2179, 'ηγεμονευω', 2448, '2230', 'ἡγεμονεύω', 'hēgemoneuō', 2, 'to be a guide, leader, chief; in NT to hold the office of a Roman provincial governor, Lk. 2:2; 3:1*'),
(2180, 'ηγεμονια', 2449, '2231', 'ἡγεμονία', 'hēgemonia', 1, 'leadership, sovereignty; in NT a reign, Lk. 3:1*'),
(2181, 'ηγεμων', 2450, '2232', 'ἡγεμών', 'hēgemōn', 20, 'a guide; a leader; a chieftain, prince, Mt. 2:6; a Roman provincial governor, under whatever title, Mt. 10:18; 27:2; Lk. 20:20; Acts 23:24 '),
(2182, 'ηγεομαι', 2451, '2233', 'ἡγέομαι', 'hēgeomai', 28, 'to lead the way; to take the lead, Acts 14:12; to be chief, to preside, govern, rule, Mt. 2:6; Acts 7:10; ἡγούμενος, a chief officer in the church, Heb. 13:7, 17, 24; also, to think, consider, count, esteem, regard, Acts 26:2; 2 Cor. 9:5 '),
(2183, 'ηδεως', 2452, '2234,2236', 'ἡδέως', 'hēdeōs', 5, 'with pleasure, gladly, willingly, Mk. 6:20; 12:37; 2 Cor. 11:19'),
(2184, 'ηδη', 2453, '2235', 'ἤδη', 'ēdē', 62, 'before now, now, already, Mt. 3:10; 5:28; ἤδη ποτέ, at length, Rom. 1:10; Phil. 4:10'),
(2185, 'ηδονη', 2454, '2237', 'ἡδονή', 'hēdonē', 5, 'pleasure, gratification; esp. sensual pleasure, Lk. 8:14; Tit. 3:3; Jas. 4:3; 2 Pet. 2:13; a passion, Jas. 4:1*'),
(2186, 'ηδυοσμον', 2455, '2238', 'ἡδύοσμον', 'hēdyosmon', 2, 'garden mint, Mt. 23:23; Lk. 11:42*'),
(2187, 'ηθος', 2456, '2239', 'ἦθος', 'ēthos', 1, 'pr. a place of customary resort; hence, a settled habit of mind and manners, 1 Cor. 15:33*'),
(2188, 'ηκω', 2457, '2240', 'ἥκω', 'hēkō', 26, 'to become, have arrived, Mt. 8:11; Mk. 8:3; Lk. 15:27; Rev. 15:4* '),
(2189, 'ηλι', 2459, '2242', 'Ἠλί', 'ēli', 1, 'Heli, the father of Joseph, Lk. 3:23*'),
(2190, 'ηλιας', 2460, '2243', 'Ἠλίας', 'ēlias', 29, 'Elijah, pr name, (1 Ki. 17-20), Mt. 11:14; 17:3f.; Mk. 15:35f.; Lk. 1:7; Jn. 1:21; Jas. 5:17'),
(2191, 'ηλικια', 2461, '2244', 'ἡλικία', 'hēlikia', 8, 'a particular period of life; the period fitted for a particular function, prime, Heb. 11:11; full age, years of discretion, Jn. 9:21, 23; perhaps, the whole duration of life, Mt. 6:27; Lk. 12:25; otherwise, stature, Lk. 2:52; 19:3; Eph. 4:13*'),
(2192, 'ηλικος', 2462, '2245', 'ἡλίκος', 'hēlikos', 3, 'as great as; how great, Col. 2:1; Jas. 3:5 (2x)*'),
(2193, 'ηλιος', 2463, '2246', 'ἥλιος', 'hēlios', 32, 'the sun, Mt. 13:43; 17:2; Mk. 1:32; meton. light of the sun, light, Acts 13:11 '),
(2194, 'ηλος', 2464, '2247', 'ἧλος', 'hēlos', 2, 'a nail, Jn. 20:25 (2x)*'),
(2195, 'ημερα', 2465, '2250', 'ἡμέρα', 'hēmera', 389, 'day, a day, the interval from sunrise to sunset, opp. to νύξ, Mt. 4:2; 12:40; Lk. 2:44; the interval of twenty-four hours, comprehending day and night, Mt. 6:34; 15:32; from the Hebrew, ἡμέρᾳ καὶ ἡμέρᾳ, day by day, every day, 2 Cor. 4:16; ἡμέραν ἐξ ἡμέρας, from day to day, continually, 2 Pet. 2:8; καθ’ ἡμέραν, every day, daily, Acts 17:17; Heb. 3:13; a point or period of time, Lk. 19:42; Acts 15:7; Eph. 6:13; a judgement, trial, 1 Cor. 4:3 '),
(2196, 'ημετερος', 2466, '2251', 'ἡμέτερος', 'hēmeteros', 7, 'our, Lk. 16:12; Acts 2:11; 24:6; 26:5; Rom. 15:4; 2 Tim. 4:15; Tit. 3:14; 1 Jn. 1:3; 2:2*'),
(2197, 'ημιθανης', 2467, '2253', 'ἡμιθανής', 'hēmithanēs', 1, 'half dead, Lk. 10:30*'),
(2198, 'ημισυς', 2468, '2255', 'ἥμισυς', 'hēmisys', 5, 'half, Mk. 6:23; Lk. 19:8; Rev. 11:9, 11; 12:14*'),
(2199, 'ημιωριον', 2469, '2256', 'ἡμιώριον', 'hēmiōrion', 1, 'also spelled ἡμίωρον, half an hour, Rev. 8:1*'),
(2200, 'ηνικα', 2471, '2259', 'ἡνίκα', 'hēnika', 2, 'when, 2 Cor. 3:15, 16*'),
(2201, 'ηπερ', 2472, '2260', 'ἤπερ', 'ēper', 1, 'strengthened form of ἤ, than, Jn. 12:43*'),
(2202, 'ηπιος', 2473, '2261', 'ἤπιος', 'ēpios', 2, 'mild, gentle, kind, 2 Tim. 2:24; 1 Thess. 2:7*'),
(2203, 'ηρ', 2474, '2262', 'Ἤρ', 'ēr', 1, 'Er, pr. name, indecl., Lk. 3:28*'),
(2204, 'ηρεμος', 2475, '2263', 'ἤρεμος', 'ēremos', 1, 'tranquil, quiet, 1 Tim. 2:2*'),
(2205, 'ηρωδης', 2476, '2264', 'Ἡρῴδης', 'hērōdēs', 43, 'Herod, pr. name. (1) Herod the Great, Mt. 2:1. (2) Herod Antipas, tetrarch of Galilee and Peraea, Mt. 14:1. (3) Herod Agrippa, Acts 12:1'),
(2206, 'ηρωδιανοι', 2477, '2265', 'Ἡρῳδιανοί', 'hērōidianoi', 3, 'Herodians, partisans of Ἡρῴδης, Herod Antipas, Mt. 22:16; Mk. 3:6; 12:13*'),
(2207, 'ηρωδιας', 2478, '2266', 'Ἡρῳδιάς', 'hērōidias', 6, 'Herodias, pr. name, the wife of Herod Antipas, Mt. 14:3, 6; Mk. 6:17, 19, 22; Lk. 3:19*'),
(2208, 'ηρωδιων', 2479, '2267', 'Ἡρῳδίων', 'hērōidiōn', 1, 'Herodian, pr. name, Rom. 16:11*'),
(2209, 'ησαιας', 2480, '2268', 'Ἠσαίας', 'ēsaias', 22, 'Isaiah, pr. name, Mt. 3:3; 13:14; Mk. 1:2; Lk. 4:17; Jn. 1:23; 12:38, 39, 41; Acts 8:28; Rom. 9:27, 29'),
(2210, 'ησαυ', 2481, '2269', 'Ἠσαῦ', 'ēsau', 3, 'Esau, pr. name, indecl. (Gen. 27-28), Rom. 9:13; Heb. 11:20; 12:16*'),
(2211, 'ησσων', 2482, '2269', 'ἥσσων', 'hēssōn', 2, 'lesser, inferior, weaker, 1 Cor. 11:17; 2 Cor. 12:15*'),
(2212, 'ησυχαζω', 2483, '2270', 'ἡσυχάζω', 'hēsychazō', 5, 'to be still, at rest; to live peaceably, be quiet, 1 Thess. 4:11; to rest from labor, Lk. 23:56; to be silent or quiet, acquiesce, to desist from discussion, Lk. 14:4; Acts 11:18; 21:14*'),
(2213, 'ησυχια', 2484, '2271', 'ἡσυχία', 'hēsychia', 4, 'rest, quiet, tranquillity; a quiet, tranquil life, 2 Thess. 3:12; silence, silent attention, Acts 22:2; 1 Tim. 2:11, 12*'),
(2214, 'ησυχιος', 2485, '2272', 'ἡσύχιος', 'hēsychios', 2, 'quiet, tranquil, peaceful, 1 Tim. 2:2; 1 Pet. 3:4*'),
(2215, 'ητοι', 2486, '2273', 'ἤτοι', 'ētoi', 1, 'whether, with an elevated tone, Rom. 6:16*'),
(2216, 'ητταομαι', 2487, '2274', 'ἡττάομαι', 'hēttaomai', 2, 'to be less, inferior to; to fare worse; by impl. to be overcome, vanquished, 2 Pet. 2:19, 20*'),
(2217, 'ηττημα', 2488, '2275', 'ἥττημα', 'hēttēma', 2, 'an inferiority, to a particular standard; default, defeat, failure, shortcoming, Rom. 11:12; 1 Cor. 6:7*'),
(2218, 'ηχεω', 2490, '2278', 'ἠχέω', 'ēcheō', 1, 'to sound, ring, 1 Cor. 13:1*'),
