(3829, 'περιεχω', 4321, '4023', 'περιέχω', 'periechō', 2, 'to encompass, enclose; met. to encompass, seize on the mind, Lk. 5:9; περιέχει, impers. it is contained, it is among the contents of a writing, 1 Pet. 2:6*'),
(3830, 'περιζωννυμι', 4322, '4024', 'περιζώννυμι', 'perizōnnymi', 6, 'also spelled περιζωννύω, to bind around with a girdle, gird; in NT mid. to gird one’s self in preparation for bodily motion and exertion, Lk. 12:37; 17:8; to wear a girdle, Rev. 1:13; 15:6'),
(3831, 'περιθεσις', 4324, '4025', 'περίθεσις', 'perithesis', 1, 'a putting on, wearing of dress, etc., 1 Pet. 3:3*'),
(3832, 'περιιστημι', 4325, '4026', 'περιίστημι', 'periistēmi', 4, 'to place around; intrans. 2 aor. περιέστην, perf. part. περιεστώς, to stand around, Jn. 11:42; Acts 25:7; mid. to keep aloof from, avoid, shun, 2 Tim. 2:16; Tit. 3:9*'),
(3833, 'περικαθαρμα', 4326, '4027', 'περικάθαρμα', 'perikatharma', 1, 'pr. filth; met. refuse, outcast, 1 Cor. 4:13*'),
(3834, 'περικαλυπτω', 4328, '4028', 'περικαλύπτω', 'perikalyptō', 3, 'to cover round about, cover over; to cover the face, Mk. 14:65; to blindfold, Lk. 22:64; pass. to be overlaid, Heb. 9:4*'),
(3835, 'περικειμαι', 4329, '4029', 'περίκειμαι', 'perikeimai', 5, 'to lie around, be surround, Heb. 12:1; to be hung around, Mk. 9:42; Lk. 17:2; to have around one’s self, to wear, Acts 28:20; to be in submission to, Heb. 5:2*'),
(3836, 'περικεφαλαια', 4330, '4030', 'περικεφαλαία', 'perikephalaia', 2, 'a helmet, Eph. 6:17; 1 Thess. 5:8*'),
(3837, 'περικρατης', 4331, '4031', 'περικρατής', 'perikratēs', 1, 'overpowering; περικρατὴς γενέσθαι, to become master of, to secure, Acts 27:16*'),
(3838, 'περικρυβω', 4332, '4032', 'περικρύβω', 'perikrybō', 1, 'also spelled περικρύπτω, to hide or keep from sight, to conceal by envelopment; to conceal, Lk. 1:24*'),
(3839, 'περικυκλοω', 4333, '4033', 'περικυκλόω', 'perikykloō', 1, 'to encircle, surround, Lk. 19:43*'),
(3840, 'περιλαμπω', 4334, '4034', 'περιλάμπω', 'perilampō', 2, 'to shine around, Lk. 2:9; Acts 26:13*'),
(3841, 'περιλειπομαι', 4335, '4035', 'περιλείπομαι', 'perileipomai', 2, 'to leave remaining; pass. to remain, survive, 1 Thess. 4:15, 17*'),
(3842, 'περιλυπος', 4337, '4036', 'περίλυπος', 'perilypos', 5, 'greatly grieved, exceedingly sorrowful, Mt. 26:38; Mk. 14:34'),
(3843, 'περιμενω', 4338, '4037', 'περιμένω', 'perimenō', 1, 'to await, wait for, Acts 1:4*'),
(3844, 'περιξ', 4339, '4038', 'πέριξ', 'perix', 1, 'neighboring, Acts 5:16*'),
(3845, 'περιοικεω', 4340, '4039', 'περιοικέω', 'perioikeō', 1, 'to dwell around, or in the vicinity; to be a neighbor, Lk. 1:65*'),
(3846, 'περιοικος', 4341, '4040', 'περίοικος', 'perioikos', 1, 'one who dwells in the vicinity, a neighbor, Lk. 1:58*'),
(3847, 'περιουσιος', 4342, '4041', 'περιούσιος', 'periousios', 1, 'chosen; peculiar, special, Tit. 2:14*'),
(3848, 'περιοχη', 4343, '4042', 'περιοχή', 'periochē', 1, 'lit., a compass, circumference, contents; fig., a section, a portion of Scripture, Acts 8:32*'),
(3849, 'περιπατεω', 4344, '4043', 'περιπατέω', 'peripateō', 95, 'pluperfect, περι[ε]πεπατήκει (3 sg), to walk, walk about, Mt. 9:5; 11:5; 14:25, 26, 29; to rove, roam, 1 Pet. 5:8; with μετά, to accompany, follow, Jn. 6:66; Rev. 3:4; to walk, frequent a locality, Jn. 7:1; 11:54; from the Hebrew, to maintain a certain walk of life and conduct, Gal. 5:16; Eph. 2:10 '),
(3850, 'περιπειρω', 4345, '4044', 'περιπείρω', 'peripeirō', 1, 'to put on a spit, transfix; met. to pierce, wound deeply, 1 Tim. 6:10*'),
(3851, 'περιπιπτω', 4346, '4045', 'περιπίπτω', 'peripiptō', 3, 'to fall around or upon, to fall in with, Lk. 10:30; to fall into, light upon, Acts 27:41; to be involved in, Jas. 1:2*'),
(3852, 'περιποιεω', 4347, '4046', 'περιποιέω', 'peripoieō', 3, 'to cause to remain over and above, to reserve, save, Lk. 17:33; mid. to acquire, gain, earn, 1 Tim. 3:13; to purchase, Acts 20:28*'),
(3853, 'περιποιησις', 4348, '4047', 'περιποίησις', 'peripoiēsis', 5, 'a laying up, keeping; an acquiring or obtaining, acquisition, 1 Thess. 5:9; 2 Thess. 2:14; a saving, preservation, Heb. 10:39; a peculiar possession, specialty, Eph. 1:14; 1 Pet. 2:9*'),
(3854, 'περιρηγνυμι', 4351, '4048', 'περιρήγνυμι', 'perirēgnymi', 1, 'also spelled περιρρήγνυμι, to break or tear all around; to strip off, Acts 16:22*'),
(3855, 'περισπαω', 4352, '4049', 'περισπάω', 'perispaō', 1, 'to draw off from around; to wheel about; to distract; pass. to be distracted, over busied, Lk. 10:40*'),
(3856, 'περισσεια', 4353, '4050', 'περισσεία', 'perisseia', 4, 'superabundance, Rom. 5:17; 2 Cor. 8:2; 10:15; Jas. 1:21*'),
(3857, 'περισσευμα', 4354, '4051', 'περίσσευμα', 'perisseuma', 5, 'more than enough, residue over and above, Mk. 8:8; abundance, exuberance, Mt. 12:34; Lk. 6:45; superabundance, affluence, 2 Cor. 8:14*'),
(3858, 'περισσευω', 4355, '4052', 'περισσεύω', 'perisseuō', 39, 'to be over and above, to be superfluous, Mt. 14:20; Mk. 12:44; Lk. 21:4; to exist in full quantity, to abound, be abundant, Rom. 5:15; 2 Cor. 1:5; to increase, be augmented, Acts 16:5; to be advanced, be rendered more prominent, Rom. 3:7; of persons, to be abundantly gifted, richly furnished, abound, Lk. 15:17; Rom. 15:13; 1 Cor. 14:12; 2 Cor. 8:7; to be possessed of a full sufficiency, Phil. 4:12, 18; to abound in performance, 1 Cor. 15:58; to be a gainer, 1 Cor. 8:8; in NT trans., to cause to be abundant, 2 Cor. 4:15; 9:8; Eph. 1:8; to cause to be abundantly furnished, cause to abound, 1 Thess. 3:12; pass. to be gifted with abundance, Mt. 13:12; 25:29 '),
(3859, 'περισσος', 4356, '4053', 'περισσός', 'perissos', 6, 'over and above, Mt. 5:37; superfluous, 2 Cor. 9:1; extraordinary, Mt. 5:47; compar. more, greater, Mt. 11:9; 23:14; excessive, 2 Cor. 2:7; adverbially, περισσόν, in full abundance, Jn. 10:10; περισσότερον, and ἐκ περισσοῦ, exceedingly, vehemently, Mk. 6:51; 7:36; 1 Cor. 15:10; Eph. 3:20; τὸ περισσόν, preeminence, advantage, Rom. 3:1'),
(3860, 'περισσοτερος', 4358, '4055', 'περισσότερος', 'perissoteros', 16, 'comparative adj. from περισσός, greater, more, Mk. 12:40; Lk. 20:47; even more, Lk. 12:48; 1 Cor. 15:10; even more, so much more, Mk. 7:36 '),
(3861, 'περισσοτερως', 4359, '4056', 'περισσοτέρως', 'perissoterōs', 12, 'more, more abundantly, more earnestly, more vehemently, 2 Cor. 7:13; exceedingly, Gal. 1:14 '),
(3862, 'περισσως', 4360, '4057', 'περισσῶς', 'perissōs', 4, 'much, abundantly, vehemently, Acts 26:11; more, more abundantly, Mt. 27:23; Mk. 10:26; 15:14*'),
(3863, 'περιστερα', 4361, '4058', 'περιστερά', 'peristera', 10, 'a dove, pigeon, Mt. 3:16; 10:16 '),
(3864, 'περιτεμνω', 4362, '4059', 'περιτέμνω', 'peritemnō', 17, 'to cut around; to circumcise, remove the prepuce, Lk. 1:59; 2:21; met. Col. 2:11; mid. to submit to circumcision, Acts 15:1 '),
(3865, 'περιτιθημι', 4363, '4060', 'περιτίθημι', 'peritithēmi', 8, 'to place around, put about or around, Mt. 21:33; 27:28; met. to attach, bestow, 1 Cor. 12:23'),
(3866, 'περιτομη', 4364, '4061', 'περιτομή', 'peritomē', 36, 'circumcision, the act or custom of circumcision, Jn. 7:22, 23; Acts 7:8; the state of being circumcised, the being circumcised, Rom. 2:25, 26, 27; 4:10; meton. the circumcision, those who are circumcised, Rom. 3:30; 4:9 met. spiritual circumcision of the heart and affection, Rom. 2:29; Col. 2:11; meton. persons spiritually circumcised, Phil. 3:3 See circumcision.'),
(3867, 'περιτρεπω', 4365, '4062', 'περιτρέπω', 'peritrepō', 1, 'to turn about; to bring round into any state, Acts 26:24*'),
(3868, 'περιτρεχω', 4366, '4063', 'περιτρέχω', 'peritrechō', 1, 'to run about, run up and down, Mk. 6:55*'),
(3869, 'περιφερω', 4367, '4064', 'περιφέρω', 'peripherō', 3, 'to bear or carry about, Mk. 6:55; 2 Cor. 4:10; pass. to be borne about hither and thither, driven to and fro, Eph. 4:14*'),
(3870, 'περιφρονεω', 4368, '4065', 'περιφρονέω', 'periphroneō', 1, 'to contemplate, reflect on; to despise, disregard, Tit. 2:15*'),
(3871, 'περιχωρος', 4369, '4066', 'περίχωρος', 'perichōros', 9, 'neighboring; ἡ περίχωρος, i.e. γῆ, an adjacent region, country round about, Mt. 14:35; Mk. 1:28; meton. inhabitants of the region round about, Mt. 3:5'),
(3872, 'περιψημα', 4370, '4067', 'περίψημα', 'peripsēma', 1, 'filth which is wiped off; met. 1 Cor. 4:13*'),
(3873, 'περπερευομαι', 4371, '4068', 'περπερεύομαι', 'perpereuomai', 1, 'to vaunt one’s self, 1 Cor. 13:4*'),
(3874, 'περσις', 4372, '4069', 'Περσίς', 'Persis', 1, 'Persis, pr. name, Rom. 16:12*'),
(3875, 'περυσι', 4373, '4070', 'πέρυσι', 'perysi', 2, 'last year, a year ago, 2 Cor. 8:10; 9:2*'),
(3876, 'πετεινον', 4374, '4071', 'πετεινόν', 'peteinon', 14, 'a bird, fowl, Mt. 6:26; 8:20 '),
(3877, 'πετομαι', 4375, '4072', 'πέτομαι', 'petomai', 5, 'also spelled πετάομαι, to fly, Rev. 4:7; 8:13; 12:14; 14:6; 19:17*'),
(3878, 'πετρα', 4376, '4073', 'πέτρα', 'petra', 15, 'a rock, Mt. 7:24, 25; met. Rom. 9:33; 1 Pet. 2:8; crags, clefts, Rev. 6:15, 16; stony ground, Lk. 8:6, 13 '),
(3879, 'πετρος', 4377, '4074', 'Πέτρος', 'Petros', 156, 'a stone; in NT the Greek rendering of the surname Cephas, given to the Apostle Simon, and having, therefore, the same sense as πέτρα, Peter, Mt. 4:18; 8:14'),
(3880, 'πετρωδης', 4378, '4075', 'πετρώδης', 'petrōdēs', 4, 'like rock; stony, rocky, Mt. 13:5, 20; Mk. 4:5, 16*'),
(3881, 'πηγανον', 4379, '4076', 'πήγανον', 'pēganon', 1, 'rue, a plant, ruta graveolens of Linnaeus, Lk. 11:42*'),
(3882, 'πηγη', 4380, '4077', 'πηγή', 'pēgē', 11, 'a source, spring, fountain, Jas. 3:11, 12; a well, Jn. 4:6; an issue, flux, flow, Mk. 5:29; met. Jn. 4:14 '),
(3883, 'πηγνυμι', 4381, '4078', 'πήγνυμι', 'pēgnymi', 1, 'to fasten; to pitch a tent, Heb. 8:2*'),
(3884, 'πηδαλιον', 4382, '4079', 'πηδάλιον', 'pēdalion', 2, 'a rudder, Acts 27:40; Jas. 3:4*'),
(3885, 'πηλικος', 4383, '4080', 'πηλίκος', 'pēlikos', 2, 'how large, Gal. 6:11; how great in dignity, Heb. 7:4*'),
(3886, 'πηλος', 4384, '4081', 'πηλός', 'pēlos', 6, 'moist earth, mud, slime, Jn. 9:6, 11, 14, 15; clay, potter’s clay, Rom. 9:21*'),
(3887, 'πηρα', 4385, '4082', 'πήρα', 'pēra', 6, 'a leather bag or sack for provisions, wallet, Mt. 10:10; Mk. 6:8'),
(3888, 'πηχυς', 4388, '4083', 'πῆχυς', 'pēchus', 4, 'pr. cubitus, the forearm; hence, a cubit, a measure of length, equal to the distance from the elbow to the extremity of the middle finger, usually considered as equivalent to a foot and one half, or 17 inches and one half, Jn. 21:8; Rev. 21:17; met. of time, a span, Mt. 6:27; Lk. 12:25*'),
(3889, 'πιαζω', 4389, '4084', 'πιάζω', 'piazō', 12, 'to press; in NT to take or lay hold of, Acts 3:7; to take, catch fish, etc., Jn. 21:3, 10; Rev. 19:20; to take, seize, apprehend, arrest, Jn. 7:30, 32, 44 '),
(3890, 'πιεζω', 4390, '4085', 'πιέζω', 'piezō', 1, 'to press, to press or squeeze down, make compact by pressure, Lk. 6:38*'),
(3891, 'πιθανολογια', 4391, '4086', 'πιθανολογία', 'pithanologia', 1, 'persuasive speech, plausible discourse, Col. 2:4*'),
(3892, 'πικραινω', 4393, '4087', 'πικραίνω', 'pikrainō', 4, 'to embitter, render bitter, Rev. 10:9; pass. to be embittered, be made bitter, Rev. 8:11; 10:10; met. pass. to be embittered, to grow angry, harsh, Col. 3:19*'),
(3893, 'πικρια', 4394, '4088', 'πικρία', 'pikria', 4, 'bitterness, Acts 8:23; Heb. 12:15; met. bitterness of spirit and language, harshness, Rom. 3:14; Eph. 4:31*'),
(3894, 'πικρος', 4395, '4089', 'πικρός', 'pikros', 2, 'bitter, Jas. 3:11; met. bitter, harsh, Jas. 3:14*'),
(3895, 'πικρως', 4396, '4090', 'πικρῶς', 'pikrōs', 2, 'bitterly, Mt. 26:75; Lk. 22:62*'),
(3896, 'πιλατος', 4397, '4091', 'Πιλᾶτος', 'Pilatos', 55, 'Pilate, pr. name'),
(3897, 'πιμπλημι', 4398, '4091', 'πίμπλημι', 'pimplēmi', 24, 'to fill, Mt. 27:48; pass. to be filled mentally, be under full influence, Lk. 1:15; 4:28; to be fulfilled, Lk. 21:22; of stated time, to be brought to a close, arrive at its close, Lk. 1:23, 57; 2:6, 21, 22 '),
(3898, 'πιμπρημι', 4399, '4092', 'πίμπρημι', 'pimprēmi', 1, 'to set on fire, burn, inflame; in NT pass., to swell from inflamation, Acts 28:6*'),
(3899, 'πινακιδιον', 4400, '4093', 'πινακίδιον', 'pinakidion', 1, 'a small tablet for writing, Lk. 1:63*'),
(3900, 'πιναξ', 4402, '4094', 'πίναξ', 'pinax', 5, 'pr. a board or plank; in NT a plate, platter, dish on which food was served, Mk. 14:8, 11'),
(3901, 'πινω', 4403, '4095', 'πίνω', 'pinō', 73, 'to drink, Mt. 6:25, 31; 26:27, 29, et al. freq.; trop. of the earth, to drink in, imbibe, Heb. 6:7 '),
(3902, 'πιοτης', 4404, '4096', 'πιότης', 'piotēs', 1, 'fatness, richness, Rom. 11:17*'),
(3903, 'πιπρασκω', 4405, '4097', 'πιπράσκω', 'pipraskō', 9, 'to sell, Mt. 13:46; 18:25; met. with ὑπό, pass. to be sold under, to be a slave to, be devoted to, Rom. 7:14');
INSERT INTO `mounce` (`id`, `word`, `gkNr`, `strongs`, `lemma`, `transliteration`, `frequenceyCount`, `definition`) VALUES
(3904, 'πιπτω', 4406, '0', 'πίπτω', 'piptō', 90, 'to fall, Mt. 15:27; Lk. 10:18; to fall, fall prostrate, fall down, Mt. 17:6; 18:29; Lk. 17:16; to fall down dead, Lk. 21:24; to fall, fall in ruins, Mt. 7:25, 27; Lk. 11:17; met. to fall, come by chance, as a lot, Acts 1:26; to fall, to fail, become null and void, fall to the ground, Lk. 16:17; to fall into a worse state, Rev. 2:5; to come to ruin, Rom. 11:11; Heb. 4:11; to fall into sin, Rom. 11:22; 1 Cor. 10:2; to fall in judgment, by condemnation, Rev. 14:8; to fall upon, seize, Rev. 11:11; to light upon, Rev. 7:16; to fall under, incur, Jas. 5:12 '),
(3905, 'πισιδια', 4407, '4099', 'Πισιδία', 'Pisidia', 1, 'Pisidia, a country of Asia Minor, Acts 14:24*'),
(3906, 'πιστευω', 4409, '4100', 'πιστεύω', 'pisteuō', 241, 'pluperfect, πεπιστεύκειν, to believe, give credit to, Mk. 1:15; 16:13; Lk. 24:25; intrans. to believe, have a mental persuasion, Mt. 8:13; 9:28; Jas. 2:19; to believe, be of opinion, Rom. 14:2; in NT πιστεύειν ἐν, εἰς, ἐπί, to believe in or on, Mt. 18:6; 27:42; Jn. 3:15, 16, 18; absol. to believe, be a believer, Acts 2:44; 4:4, 32; 13:48; trans. to intrust, commit to the charge or power of, Lk. 16:11; Jn. 2:24; pass. to be intrusted with, Rom. 3:2; 1 Cor. 9:17 '),
(3907, 'πιστικος', 4410, '4101', 'πιστικός', 'pistikos', 2, 'genuine, unadulterated, pure, Mk. 14:3; Jn. 12:3*'),
(3908, 'πιστις', 4411, '4102', 'πίστις', 'pistis', 243, 'faith, belief, firm persuasion, 2 Cor. 5:7; Heb. 11:1; assurance, firm conviction, Rom. 14:23; ground of belief, guarantee, assurance, Acts 17:31; good faith, honesty, integrity, Mt. 23:23; Gal. 5:22; Tit. 2:10; faithfulness, truthfulness, Rom. 3:3; in NT faith in God and Christ, Mt. 8:10; Acts 3:16, et al. freq.; ἡ πίστις, the matter of Gospel faith, Acts 6:7; Jude 3 '),
(3909, 'πιστος', 4412, '4103', 'πιστός', 'pistos', 67, 'faithful, true, trusty, Mt. 24:45; 25:21, 23; Lk. 12:42; 2 Tim. 2:2; put in trust, 1 Cor. 7:25; true, veracious, Rev. 1:5; 2:13; credible, sure, certain, indubitable, Acts 13:34; 1 Tim. 1:15; believing, yielding belief and confidence, Jn. 20:27; Gal. 3:9; spc. a Christian believer, Acts 10:45; 16:1, 15; 2 Cor. 6:15; πιστόν, in a true-hearted manner, right-mindedly, 3 Jn. 5 '),
(3910, 'πιστοω', 4413, '4104', 'πιστόω', 'pistoō', 1, 'to make trustworthy; pass. to be assured, feel sure belief, 2 Tim. 3:14*'),
(3911, 'πλαναω', 4414, '4105', 'πλανάω', 'planaō', 39, 'to lead astray, cause to wander; pass. to go astray, wander about, stray, Mt. 18:12, 13; 1 Pet. 2:25; met. to mislead, deceive, Mt. 24:4, 5, 11, 24; pass. to be deceived, err, mistake, Mt. 22:29; to seduce, delude, Jn. 7:12; pass. to be seduced or wander from the path of virtue, to sin, transgress, Tit. 3:3; Heb. 5:2; Jas. 5:19 '),
(3912, 'πλανη', 4415, '4106', 'πλάνη', 'planē', 10, 'a wandering; deceit, deception, delusion, imposture, fraud, Mt. 27:64; 1 Thess. 2:3; seduction, deceiving, Eph. 4:14; 2 Thess. 2:11; 1 Jn. 4:6; error, false opinion, 2 Pet. 3:17; wandering from the path of truth and virtue, perverseness, wickedness, sin, Rom. 1:27; Jas. 5:20; 2 Pet. 2:18; Jude 11* '),
(3913, 'πλανητης', 4417, '4107', 'πλανήτης', 'planētēs', 1, 'a rover, roving, a wanderer, wandering; ἀστὴρ πλανήτης, a wandering star, Jude 13*'),
(3914, 'πλανος', 4418, '4108', 'πλάνος', 'planos', 5, 'a wanderer, vagabond; also act. deceiving, seducing; a deceiver, impostor, Mt. 27:63; 2 Cor. 6:8; 1 Tim. 4:1; 2 Jn. 7*'),
(3915, 'πλαξ', 4419, '4109', 'πλάξ', 'plax', 3, 'a flat broad surface; a table, tablet, 2 Cor. 3:3; Heb. 9:4*'),
(3916, 'πλασμα', 4420, '4110', 'πλάσμα', 'plasma', 1, 'a thing formed or fashioned; spc. a potter’s vessel, Rom. 9:20*'),
(3917, 'πλασσω', 4421, '4111', 'πλάσσω', 'plassō', 2, 'to form, fashion, mould, Rom. 9:20; 1 Tim. 2:13*'),
(3918, 'πλαστος', 4422, '4112', 'πλαστός', 'plastos', 1, 'formed, fashioned, moulded; met. fabricated, counterfeit, delusive, 2 Pet. 2:3*'),
(3919, 'πλατεια', 4423, '4113', 'πλατεῖα', 'plateia', 9, 'a street, broad way, Mt. 6:5; 12:19; Lk. 10:10 '),
(3920, 'πλατος', 4424, '4114', 'πλάτος', 'platos', 4, 'breadth, Eph. 3:18; Rev. 20:9; 21:16*'),
(3921, 'πλατυνω', 4425, '4115', 'πλατύνω', 'platynō', 3, 'to make broad, widen, enlarge, Mt. 23:5; pass. met. of the heart, from the Hebrew, to be expanded with kindly and genial feelings, 2 Cor. 6:11, 13*'),
(3922, 'πλατυς', 4426, '4116', 'πλατύς', 'platys', 1, 'broad, wide, Mt. 7:13*'),
(3923, 'πλεγμα', 4427, '4117', 'πλέγμα', 'plegma', 1, 'anything plaited or intertwined; a braid of hair, 1 Tim. 2:9*'),
(3924, 'πλεκω', 4428, '4120', 'πλέκω', 'plekō', 3, 'to interweave, weave, braid, plait, Mt. 27:29; Mk. 15:17; Jn. 19:2*'),
