(4392, 'σικερα', 4975, '4608', 'σίκερα', 'sikera', 1, 'strong or inebriating drink, Lk. 1:15*'),
(4393, 'σιλας', 4976, '4609', 'Σίλας', 'Silas', 12, 'Silas, pr. name, in Luke, Acts 15:22; see Σιλουανός'),
(4394, 'σιλουανος', 4977, '4610', 'Σιλουανός', 'Silouanos', 4, 'Silvanus, pr. name, 2 Cor. 1:19; 1 Thess. 1:1; 2 Thess. 1:1; 1 Pet. 5:12, see Σίλας*'),
(4395, 'σιλωαμ', 4978, '4611', 'Σιλωάμ', 'Silōam', 3, 'Siloam, a pool or fountain near Jerusalem, Lk. 13:4; Jn. 9:7, 11*'),
(4396, 'σιμικινθιον', 4980, '4612', 'σιμικίνθιον', 'simikinthion', 1, 'an apron, Acts 19:12*'),
(4397, 'σιμων', 4981, '4613', 'Σίμων', 'Simōn', 75, 'Simon, pr. name. (1) Simon Peter, Mt. 4:18. (2) Simon (the Canaanite) the Zealot, Mt. 10:4; Acts 1:13 . (3) Simon, brother of Jesus, Mt. 13:55; Mk. 6:3. (4) Simon, the leper, Mt. 26:6; Mk. 14:3. (5) Simon, the Pharisee, Lk. 7:40. (6) Simon of Cyrene, Mt. 27:32. (7) Simon, father of Judas Iscariot, Jn. 6:71. (8) Simon, the sorcerer, Acts 8:9. (9) Simon, the tanner, of Joppa, Acts 9:43; 10:6'),
(4398, 'σινα', 4982, '4614', 'Σινά', 'Sina', 4, 'Mount Sinai, in Arabia, Acts 7:30, 38; Gal. 4:24, 25*'),
(4399, 'σιναπι', 4983, '4615', 'σίναπι', 'sinapi', 5, 'mustard; in NT probably the shrub, not the herb, Khardal, Salvadora Persica L., the fruit of which possesses the pungency of mustard, Mt. 13:31; 17:20; Mk. 4:31; Lk. 13:19; 17:6*'),
(4400, 'σινδων', 4984, '4616', 'σινδών', 'sindōn', 6, 'sindon; pr. fine Indian cloth; fine linen; in NT a linen garment, an upper garment or wrapper of fine linen, worn in summer by night, and used to envelope dead bodies, Mt. 27:59; Mk. 14:51, 52; 15:46; Lk. 23:53*'),
(4401, 'σινιαζω', 4985, '4617', 'σινιάζω', 'siniazō', 1, 'to sift; met. to sift by trials and temptations, Lk. 22:31*'),
(4402, 'σιρικος', 4986, '4596', 'σιρικός', 'sirikos', 1, 'see also σηρικός, silk, of silk, silken; τὸ σηρικόν, silken stuff, Rev. 18:12*'),
(4403, 'σιτευτος', 4988, '4618', 'σιτευτός', 'siteutos', 3, 'fed, fatted, Lk. 15:23, 27, 30*'),
(4404, 'σιτιον', 4989, '4618', 'σιτίον', 'sition', 1, 'provision of corn, food, Acts 7:12*'),
(4405, 'σιτιστος', 4990, '4619', 'σιτιστός', 'sitistos', 1, 'fatted, a fatling, cattle, Mt. 22:4*'),
(4406, 'σιτομετριον', 4991, '4620', 'σιτομέτριον', 'sitometrion', 1, 'a certain measure of grain distributed for food at set times to the slaves of a family, a ration, Lk. 12:42*'),
(4407, 'σιτος', 4992, '4621', 'σῖτος', 'sitos', 14, 'corn, grain, wheat, Mt. 3:12; 13:25, 29, 30; Mk. 4:28 '),
(4408, 'σιων', 4994, '4622', 'Σιών', 'Siōn', 7, 'Zion, Mt. Zion, a hill within the city of Jerusalem, indecl., Heb. 12:22; Rev. 14:1; poetic use, Mt. 21:5; Jn. 12:15; people of Israel, Rom. 9:33; 11:26; new Jerusalem of Christianity, 1 Pet. 2:6*'),
(4409, 'σιωπαω', 4995, '4623', 'σιωπάω', 'siōpaō', 10, 'to be silent, keep silence, hold one’s peace, Mt. 20:31; 26:63; Mk. 3:4; 9:34; 10:48; 14:61; Lk. 19:40; Acts 18:9; σιωπῶν, silent, dumb, Lk. 1:20; met. to be silent, still, hushed, calm, as the sea, Mk. 4:39* '),
(4410, 'σκανδαλιζω', 4997, '4624', 'σκανδαλίζω', 'skandalizō', 29, 'pr. to cause to stumble; met. offend, Mt. 17:27; to offend, shock, excite feeling of repugnance, Jn. 6:61; 1 Cor. 8:13; pass. to be offended, shocked, pained, Mt. 15:12; Rom. 14:21; 2 Cor. 11:29; σκανδαλίζεσθαι ἔν τινι, to be affected with scruples of repugnance towards any one as respects his claims or pretensions, Mt. 11:6; 13:57; met. to cause to stumble morally, to cause to falter or err, Mt. 5:29; 18:6; pass. to falter, fall away, Mt. 13:21 '),
(4411, 'σκανδαλον', 4998, '4625', 'σκάνδαλον', 'skandalon', 15, 'pr. a trap-spring; also genr. a stumbling block, anything against which one stumbles, an impediment; met. a cause of ruin, destruction, misery, etc., Rom. 9:33; 11:9; 1 Pet. 2:8; a cause or occasion of sinning, Mt. 16:23; 18:7 (3x); Lk. 17:1; Rom. 14:13; 16:17; Rev. 2:14; scandal, offense, cause of indignation, Mt. 13:41; 1 Cor. 1:23; Gal. 5:11; 1 Jn. 2:10* '),
(4412, 'σκαπτω', 4999, '4626', 'σκάπτω', 'skaptō', 3, 'to dig, excavate, Lk. 6:48; 13:8; 16:3*'),
(4413, 'σκαφη', 5002, '4627', 'σκάφη', 'skaphē', 3, 'pr. anything excavated or hollowed; a boat, skiff, Acts 27:16, 30, 32*'),
(4414, 'σκελος', 5003, '4628', 'σκέλος', 'skelos', 3, 'the leg, Jn. 19:31, 32, 33*'),
(4415, 'σκεπασμα', 5004, '4629', 'σκέπασμα', 'skepasma', 1, 'covering; clothing, raiment, 1 Tim. 6:8*'),
(4416, 'σκευας', 5005, '4630', 'Σκευᾶς', 'Skeuas', 1, 'Sceva, pr. name, Acts 19:14*'),
(4417, 'σκευη', 5006, '4631', 'σκευή', 'skeuē', 1, 'apparatus; tackle, Acts 27:19*'),
(4418, 'σκευος', 5007, '4632', 'σκεῦος', 'skeuos', 23, 'a vessel, utensil for containing anything, Mk. 11:16; Lk. 8:16; Rom. 9:21; any utensil, instrument; σκεύη, household stuff, furniture, goods, etc., Mt. 12:29; Mk. 3:27; the mast of a ship, or, the sail, Acts 27:17; met. an instrument, means, organ, minister, Acts 9:15; σκεύη ὀργῆς and σκεύη ἐλέους, vessels of wrath, or, of mercy, persons visited by punishment, or, the divine favor, Rom. 9:22, 23; the vessel or frame of the human individual, 1 Thess. 4:4; 1 Pet. 3:7 '),
(4419, 'σκηνη', 5008, '4633', 'σκηνή', 'skēnē', 20, 'a tent, tabernacle; genr. any temporary dwelling; a tent, booth, Mt. 17:4; Heb. 11:9; the tabernacle of the covenant, Heb. 8:5; 9:1, 21; 13:10; allegor. the celestial or true tabernacle, Heb. 8:2; 9:11; a division or compartment of the tabernacle, Heb. 9:2, 3, 6; a small portable tent or shrine, Acts 7:43; an abode or seat of a lineage, Acts 15:16; a mansion, habitation, abode, dwelling, Lk. 16:9; Rev. 13:6 '),
(4420, 'σκηνοπηγια', 5009, '4634', 'σκηνοπηγία', 'skēnopēgia', 1, 'pr. a pitching of tents or booths; hence, the feast of tabernacles or booths, instituted in memory of the forty years’ wandering of the Israelites in the desert, and as a season of gratitude for the ingathering of harvest, celebrated for eight days, commencing on the 15th of Tisri, Jn. 7:2*'),
(4421, 'σκηνοποιος', 5010, '4635', 'σκηνοποιός', 'skēnopoios', 1, 'a tent-maker, Acts 18:3*'),
(4422, 'σκηνος', 5011, '4636', 'σκῆνος', 'skēnos', 2, 'a tent, tabernacle, lodging; met. the corporeal tabernacle, 2 Cor. 5:1, 4*'),
(4423, 'σκηνοω', 5012, '4637', 'σκηνόω', 'skēnoō', 5, 'to pitch tent, encamp; to tabernacle, dwell in a tent; to dwell, have one’s abode, Jn. 1:14; Rev. 7:15; 12:12; 13:6; 21:3* '),
(4424, 'σκηνωμα', 5013, '4638', 'σκήνωμα', 'skēnōma', 3, 'a habitation, abode, dwelling, Acts 7:46; the corporeal tabernacle of the soul, 2 Pet. 1:13, 14*'),
(4425, 'σκια', 5014, '4639', 'σκιά', 'skia', 7, 'a shade, shadow, Mk. 4:32; Acts 5:15; met. a shadow, a foreshadowing, a vague outline, in distinction from ἡ εἰκών, the perfect image or delineation, and τὸ σῶμα, the reality, Col. 2:17; Heb. 8:5; 10:1; gloom; σκιὰ θανάτου, death shade, the thickest darkness, Mt. 4:16; Lk. 1:79*'),
(4426, 'σκιρταω', 5015, '4640', 'σκιρτάω', 'skirtaō', 3, 'to leap, Lk. 1:41, 44; to leap, skip, bound for joy, Lk. 6:23*'),
(4427, 'σκληροκαρδια', 5016, '4641', 'σκληροκαρδία', 'sklērokardia', 3, 'hardness of heart, obstinacy, perverseness, Mt. 19:8; Mk. 10:5; 16:14*');
INSERT INTO `mounce` (`id`, `word`, `gkNr`, `strongs`, `lemma`, `transliteration`, `frequenceyCount`, `definition`) VALUES
(4428, 'σκληρος', 5017, '4642', 'σκληρός', 'sklēros', 5, 'dry, hard to the touch; met. harsh, severe, stern, Mt. 25:24; vehement, violent, fierce, Jas. 3:4; grievous, painful, Acts 26:14; grating to the mind, repulsive, offensive, Jn. 6:60; stubborn, resistance to authority, Jude 15*'),
(4429, 'σκληροτης', 5018, '4643', 'σκληρότης', 'sklērotēs', 1, 'hardness; met. σκληρότης τῆς καρδίας, hardness of heart, obstinacy, perverseness, Rom. 2:5*'),
(4430, 'σκληροτραχηλος', 5019, '4644', 'σκληροτράχηλος', 'sklērotrachēlos', 1, 'stiff-necked, obstinate, Acts 7:51*'),
(4431, 'σκληρυνω', 5020, '4645', 'σκληρύνω', 'sklērynō', 6, 'to harden; met. to harden morally, to make stubborn, Heb. 3:8, 15; 4:7; as a negation of ἐλεεῖν, to leave to stubbornness and contumacy, Rom. 9:18; mid. and pass. to put on a stubborn frame, Acts 19:9; Heb. 3:13*'),
(4432, 'σκολιος', 5021, '4646', 'σκολιός', 'skolios', 4, 'crooked, tortuous, Lk. 3:5; met. perverse, wicked, Acts 2:40; Phil. 2:15; crooked, peevish, morose, 1 Pet. 2:18*'),
(4433, 'σκολοψ', 5022, '4647', 'σκόλοψ', 'skolops', 1, 'anything pointed; met. a thorn, a plague, 2 Cor. 12:7*'),
(4434, 'σκοπεω', 5023, '4648', 'σκοπέω', 'skopeō', 6, 'to view attentively, watch; to see, observe, take care, beware, Lk. 11:35; Gal. 6:1; to regard, have respect to, 2 Cor. 4:18; Phil. 2:4; to mark, note, Rom. 16:17; Phil. 3:17*'),
(4435, 'σκοπος', 5024, '4649', 'σκοπός', 'skopos', 1, 'a watcher; also, a distant object on which the eye is kept fixed; a mark, goal, Phil. 3:14*'),
(4436, 'σκορπιος', 5026, '4651', 'σκορπίος', 'skorpios', 5, 'a scorpion, a large insect, sometimes several inches in length, shaped somewhat like a crab and furnished with a tail terminating in a stinger from which it emits a dangerous poison, Lk. 10:19; 11:12; Rev. 9:3, 5, 10*'),
(4437, 'σκοτεινος', 5027, '4652', 'σκοτεινός', 'skoteinos', 3, 'dark, Mt. 6:23; Lk. 11:34, 36*'),
(4438, 'σκοτια', 5028, '4653', 'σκοτία', 'skotia', 16, 'darkness, Jn. 6:17; 20:1; privacy, Mt. 10:27; Lk. 12:3; met. moral or spiritual darkness, Jn. 1:5 (2x); 8:12; 12:35, 46; 1 Jn. 1:5; 2:8, 9, 11* '),
(4439, 'σκοτος', 5030, '4655', 'σκότος', 'skotos', 31, 'darkness, Mt. 27:45; Acts 2:20; gloom of punishment and misery, Mt. 8:12; 2 Pet. 2:17; met. moral or spiritual darkness, Mt. 4:16; Jn. 3:19; Eph. 5:11; a realm of moral darkness, Eph. 5:8; 6:12 '),
(4440, 'σκοτοω', 5031, '4656', 'σκοτόω', 'skotoō', 3, 'to darken, shroud in darkness, Eph. 4:18; Rev. 9:2; 16:10'),
(4441, 'σκυβαλον', 5032, '4657', 'σκύβαλον', 'skybalon', 1, 'dung, sweepings, refuse, rubbish, Phil. 3:8*'),
(4442, 'σκυθης', 5033, '4658', 'Σκύθης', 'Skythēs', 1, 'A Scythian, a native of Scythia, the modern Mongolia and Tartary, Col. 3:11*'),
(4443, 'σκυθρωπος', 5034, '4659', 'σκυθρωπός', 'skythrōpos', 2, 'of a stern, morose, sour, gloomy, or dejected countenance, Mt. 6:16; Lk. 24:17*'),
(4444, 'σκυλλω', 5035, '4660', 'σκύλλω', 'skyllō', 4, 'to flay, lacerate; met. to vex, trouble, annoy, Mk. 5:35; Lk. 7:6; 8:49; pass. met. ἐσκυλμένοι, in sorry plight, Mt. 9:36*'),
(4445, 'σκυλον', 5036, '4661', 'σκῦλον', 'skylon', 1, 'spoils stripped off an enemy; σκῦλα, spoil, plunder, booty, Lk. 11:22*'),
(4446, 'σκωληκοβρωτος', 5037, '4662', 'σκωληκόβρωτος', 'skōlēkobrōtos', 1, 'eaten of worms, consumed by worms, Acts 12:23*'),
(4447, 'σκωληξ', 5038, '4663', 'σκώληξ', 'skōlēx', 1, 'a worm; met. gnawing anguish, Mk. 9:48*'),
(4448, 'σμαραγδινος', 5039, '4664', 'σμαράγδινος', 'smaragdinos', 1, 'of smaragdus or emerald, Rev. 4:3*'),
(4449, 'σμαραγδος', 5040, '4665', 'σμάραγδος', 'smaragdos', 1, 'smaragdus, the emerald, a gem of a pure green color; but under this name the ancients probably comprised all stones of a fine green color, Rev. 21:19*'),
(4450, 'σμυρνα', 5044, '4667', 'Σμύρνα', 'Smyrna', 2, 'Smyrna, a maritime city of Ionia, in Asia Minor, Rev. 1:11; 2:8*. See PhotoGuide.'),
(4451, 'σμυρνιζω', 5046, '4669', 'σμυρνίζω', 'smyrnizō', 1, 'to mingle or flavor with myrrh, Mk. 15:23*'),
(4452, 'σοδομα', 5047, '4670', 'Σόδομα', 'Sodoma', 9, 'Sodom, (Gen. 19:24) one of the four cities of the vale of Siddim, now covered by the Dead sea, Mt. 11:23f.; Lk. 17:29; Rom. 9:29; 2 Pet. 2:6; Rev. 11:8'),
(4453, 'σολομων', 5048, '4672', 'Σολομών', 'Solomōn', 12, 'Solomon, also spelled Σολομῶν, pr. name, son and successor of David, Mt. 1:6f.; 6:29; Lk. 11:31; Jn. 10:23; Acts 3:11; 7:47'),
(4454, 'σορος', 5049, '4673', 'σορός', 'soros', 1, 'a coffer; an urn for receiving the ashes of the dead; a coffin; in NT a bier, Lk. 7:14*'),
(4455, 'σος', 5050, '4674', 'σός', 'sos', 26, 'yours, Mt. 7:3, 22; οἱ σοί, your kindred, friends, etc., Mk. 5:19; τὸ σόν and τὰ σά, what is yours, your property, goods, etc., Mt. 20:14; 25:25; Lk. 6:30'),
(4456, 'σουδαριον', 5051, '4676', 'σουδάριον', 'soudarion', 4, 'a handkerchief, napkin, etc., Lk. 19:20; Jn. 11:44; 20:7; Acts 19:12*'),
(4457, 'σουσαννα', 5052, '4677', 'Σουσάννα', 'Sousanna', 1, 'Susanna, pr. name, Lk. 8:3*'),
(4458, 'σοφια', 5053, '4678', 'σοφία', 'sophia', 51, 'wisdom in general, knowledge, Mt. 12:42; Lk. 2:40, 52; 11:31; Acts 7:10; ability, Lk. 21:15; Acts 6:3, 10; practical wisdom, prudence, Col. 4:5; learning, science, Mt. 13:54; Mk. 6:2; Acts 7:22; scientific skill, 1 Cor. 1:17; 2:1; professed wisdom, human philosophy, 1 Cor. 1:19, 20, 22; 2:4, 5, 6; superior knowledge and enlightenment, Col. 2:23; in NT divine wisdom, Rom. 11:33; Eph. 3:10; Col. 2:3; revealed wisdom, Mt. 11:19; Lk. 11:49; 1 Cor. 1:24, 30; 2:7; Christian enlightenment, 1 Cor. 12:8; Eph. 1:8, 17; Col. 1:9, 28, 3:16; Jas. 1:5; 3:13 '),
(4459, 'σοφιζω', 5054, '4679', 'σοφίζω', 'sophizō', 2, 'to make wise, enlighten, 2 Tim. 3:15; mid. to invent skilfully, devise artfully, pass. 2 Pet. 1:16*'),
(4460, 'σοφος', 5055, '4680', 'σοφός', 'sophos', 20, 'wise generally, 1 Cor. 1:25; shrewd, clever, Rom. 16:19; 1 Cor. 3:10; 6:5; learned, intelligent, Mt. 11:25; Rom. 1:14, 22; 1 Cor. 1:19, 20, 26, 27; 3:18; in NT divinely instructed, Mt. 23:34; furnished with Christian wisdom, spiritually enlightened, Jas. 3:13; all wise, Rom. 16:27; 1 Tim. 1:17; Jude 25 '),
(4461, 'σπανια', 5056, '4681', 'Σπανία', 'Spania', 2, 'Spain, Rom. 15:24, 28*'),
(4462, 'σπαρασσω', 5057, '4682', 'σπαράσσω', 'sparassō', 3, 'pr. to tear, lacerate; by impl. to agitate greatly, convulse, distort by convulsion, Mk. 1:26; 9:26; Lk. 9:39*'),
(4463, 'σπαργανοω', 5058, '4683', 'σπαργανόω', 'sparganoō', 2, 'to swathe, wrap in swaddling cloths, Lk. 2:7, 12*'),
(4464, 'σπαταλαω', 5059, '4684', 'σπαταλάω', 'spatalaō', 2, 'to live luxuriously, voluptuously, wantonly, 1 Tim. 5:6; Jas. 5:5*'),
(4465, 'σπαω', 5060, '4685', 'σπάω', 'spaō', 2, 'to draw, pull; to draw a sword, Mk. 14:47; Acts 16:27*'),
(4466, 'σπειρα', 5061, '4686', 'σπεῖρα', 'speira', 7, 'anything twisted or wreathed, a cord, coil, band, etc.; a band of soldiers, company, troop; used for a Roman cohort, about 600 soldiers, Mt. 27:27; Acts 10:1; the temple guard, Mk. 15:16; Jn. 18:3, 12; Acts 21:31; 27:1*'),
(4467, 'σπειρω', 5062, '4687', 'σπείρω', 'speirō', 52, 'to sow seed, Mt. 6:26; 13:3, 4, 18, 24, 25, 27, 37, 3 '),
(4468, 'σπεκουλατωρ', 5063, '4688', 'σπεκουλάτωρ', 'spekoulatōr', 1, 'a sentinel, life-guardsman, a kind of soldiers who formed the body-guard of princes, etc., one of whose duties was to put criminals to death, Mk. 6:27*'),
(4469, 'σπενδω', 5064, '4689', 'σπένδω', 'spendō', 2, 'to pour out a libation or drink-offering; in NT mid. to make a libation of one’s self by expending energy and life in the service of the Gospel, Phil. 2:17; pass. to be in the act of being sacrificed in the cause of the Gospel, 2 Tim. 4:6*'),
(4470, 'σπερμα', 5065, '4690', 'σπέρμα', 'sperma', 43, 'seed, Mt. 13:24, 27, 37, 38; semen virile, Heb. 11:11; offspring, posterity, Mt. 22:24, 25; Jn. 7:42; a seed of future generations, Rom. 9:29; in NT met. a seed or principle of spiritual life, 1 Jn. 3:9 '),
(4471, 'σπερμολογος', 5066, '4691', 'σπερμολόγος', 'spermologos', 1, 'pr. seed-picking; one who picks up and retails scraps of information; a gossip; a babbler, Acts 17:18*'),
(4472, 'σπευδω', 5067, '4692', 'σπεύδω', 'speudō', 6, 'trans. to urge on, impel, quicken; to quicken in idea, to be eager for the arrival of, 2 Pet. 3:12; intrans. to hasten, make haste, Acts 20:16; 22:18; the part. has the force of an adverb, quickly, hastily, Lk. 2:16; 19:5, 6*'),
(4473, 'σπηλαιον', 5068, '4693', 'σπήλαιον', 'spēlaion', 6, 'a cave, cavern, den, hideout, Mt. 21:13; Mk. 11:17; Lk. 19:46; Jn. 11:38; Heb. 11:38; Rev. 6:5*'),
(4474, 'σπιλας', 5069, '4694', 'σπιλάς', 'spilas', 1, 'a sharply-cleft portion of rock; in NT a flaw, stigma, Jude 12*'),
(4475, 'σπιλος', 5070, '4696', 'σπίλος', 'spilos', 2, 'a spot, stain, blot; a moral blemish, Eph. 5:27; 2 Pet. 2:13*'),
(4476, 'σπιλοω', 5071, '4695', 'σπιλόω', 'spiloō', 2, 'to spot, soil; to contaminate, defile, Jas. 3:6; Jude 23*'),
(4477, 'σπλαγχνιζομαι', 5072, '4697', 'σπλαγχνίζομαι', 'splanchnizomai', 12, 'to be moved with pity or compassion, Mt. 9:36; 14:14; 20:34; Lk. 7:13; to be compassionate, Mt. 18:27 '),
(4478, 'σπλαγχνον', 5073, '4698', 'σπλάγχνον', 'splanchnon', 11, 'the chief intestines, viscera; the entrails, bowels, Acts 1:18; met. the heart, the affections of the heart, the tender affections, Lk. 1:78; 2 Cor. 6:12; 7:15; Phil. 1:8, 2:1; Col. 3:12; Phlm. 7, 20; 1 Jn. 3:17; meton. a cherished one, dear as one’s self, Phlm. 12* '),
(4479, 'σπογγος', 5074, '4699', 'σπόγγος', 'spongos', 3, 'a sponge, Mt. 27:48; Mk. 15:36; Jn. 19:29*'),
(4480, 'σποδος', 5075, '4700', 'σποδός', 'spodos', 3, 'ashes, Mt. 11:21; Lk. 10:13; Heb. 9:13*'),
(4481, 'σπορα', 5076, '4701', 'σπορά', 'spora', 1, 'a sowing; seed sown; met. generative seed, generation, 1 Pet. 1:23*'),
(4482, 'σποριμος', 5077, '4702', 'σπόριμος', 'sporimos', 3, 'sown, fit to be sown; in NT τὰ σπόριμα, fields which are sown, fields of grain, cornfields, Mt. 12:1; Mk. 2:23; Lk. 6:1*'),
(4483, 'σπορος', 5078, '4703', 'σπόρος', 'sporos', 6, 'a sowing; in NT seed, that which is sown, Mk. 4:26, 27; Lk. 8:5, 11; met. the seed sown in almsgiving, 2 Cor. 9:10*'),
(4484, 'σπουδαζω', 5079, '4704', 'σπουδάζω', 'spoudazō', 11, 'to hurry; be bent upon, Gal. 2:10; to endeavor earnestly, strive, Eph. 4:3 '),
(4485, 'σπουδαιος', 5080, '4705,4706,4707', 'σπουδαῖος', 'spoudaios', 3, 'earnest, eager, forward, zealous, 2 Cor. 8:17, 22 (2x)*'),
(4486, 'σπουδαιως', 5081, '4708,4709', 'σπουδαίως', 'spoudaiōs', 4, 'earnestly, eagerly, diligently, Lk. 7:4; 2 Tim. 1:17; Tit. 3:13; compar. σπουδαιοτέρως, more earnestly, with special urgency, Phil. 2:28'),
